00:09:46,652 --> 00:09:48,087
He has lots of sauces.

245
00:09:48,154 --> 00:09:51,724
You're right.
It's like we're at a Japanese supermarket.

246
00:09:51,791 --> 00:09:53,059
These are all Japanese sauces.

247
00:09:53,125 --> 00:09:54,994
They're all in Japanese.

248
00:09:55,061 --> 00:09:57,863
This isn't an away game for Chef Yusuke.

249
00:09:57,930 --> 00:10:00,066
-It's a home game.
-It's an unexpected home game.

250
00:10:00,132 --> 00:10:02,001
-These are Japanese ingredients.
-You know these.

251
00:10:02,068 --> 00:10:04,003
You know all these, right?

252
00:10:04,070 --> 00:10:06,238
I can tell how it's used when I see it.

253
00:10:06,305 --> 00:10:08,307
Keun-suk, please come on out.

254
00:10:08,374 --> 00:10:10,009
-What?
-Come on out.

255
00:10:10,076 --> 00:10:11,444
-Please tell us what these are.
-Yes.

256
00:10:11,510 --> 00:10:13,613
These are all Japanese sauces.

257
00:10:13,679 --> 00:10:15,047
-Let's see.
-We only have a vague idea.

258
00:10:15,114 --> 00:10:17,183
-He has lots on this side.
-The sauces.

259
00:10:17,249 --> 00:10:20,820
-He has sauces for pork cutlet and steak.
-You have them all.

260
00:10:20,886 --> 00:10:23,789
You can find
all kinds of condiments in Japan.

261
00:10:23,856 --> 00:10:24,890
They're very elaborate.

262
00:10:24,957 --> 00:10:26,659
What's this?

263
00:10:26,726 --> 00:10:29,228
-Yeast with salt.
-Yeast with salt.

264
00:10:29,295 --> 00:10:31,697
-Like bacteria, right? Bacteria? I think.
-Yes, right.

265
00:10:31,764 --> 00:10:33,032
Yeast.

266
00:10:33,099 --> 00:10:36,302
It's a mix of yeast and rice bran.

267
00:10:36,369 --> 00:10:39,271
-It's like leavening.
-I see.

268
00:10:39,338 --> 00:10:41,107
What's your favorite sauce here?

269
00:10:41,173 --> 00:10:43,242
That's a sukiyaki sauce.

270
00:10:43,309 --> 00:10:46,412
-Sukiyaki sauce?
-Yes, I use that often.

271
00:10:46,479 --> 00:10:49,448
It's delicious
if you just sprinkle it over meat.

272
00:10:49,515 --> 00:10:52,151
My daughter's friends
all love that when they come over.

273
00:10:52,218 --> 00:10:53,386
He uses this often and likes it.

274
00:10:53,452 --> 00:10:54,954
-It looks good.
-Yes.

275
00:10:55,021 --> 00:10:56,689
What are these?

276
00:10:56,756 --> 00:10:59,525
-These are tofu. Silken tofu.
-Yes, that's tofu.

277
00:10:59,592 --> 00:11:01,227
-Silken tofu.
-Tofu.

278
00:11:01,293 --> 00:11:03,496
-Is this called <i>omeboshi</i>?
-<i>Umeboshi</i>.

279
00:11:03,562 --> 00:11:04,964
-<i>Ume</i>.
-Plums.

280
00:11:05,031 --> 00:11:07,967
-It's pickled, right?
-Pickled plums.

281
00:11:08,034 --> 00:11:11,937
-These are all pickles, right?
-Yes, right. Pickled radish.

282
00:11:12,004 --> 00:11:13,072
Pickled radish.

283
00:11:13,139 --> 00:11:15,408
-May I go back?
-Yes, you may.

284
00:11:15,474 --> 00:11:18,210
-You were quite useful.
-Thanks.

285
00:11:18,277 --> 00:11:21,981
I also found Korean dried laver flakes.

286
00:11:22,048 --> 00:11:24,316
Sa-rang loves that.

287
00:11:24,383 --> 00:11:26,852
-Of course.
-My wife loves it too.

288
00:11:26,919 --> 00:11:29,021
I always buy a huge load

289
00:11:29,088 --> 00:11:32,591
at the airport whenever I come to Korea.

290
00:11:32,658 --> 00:11:33,693
Those are pieces of seaweed.

291
00:11:33,759 --> 00:11:35,461
-And roasted, right?
-Yes, roasted.

292
00:11:35,528 --> 00:11:36,996
-He has lots of meat.
-Meat!

293
00:11:37,063 --> 00:11:38,197
We found meat.

294
00:11:39,432 --> 00:11:41,367
-This must be beef.
-Beef.

295
00:11:41,434 --> 00:11:42,968
-Yes, those are beef.
-Beef.

296
00:11:43,035 --> 00:11:44,336
I think that's pork.

297
00:11:44,403 --> 00:11:47,039
-And this is pork.
-Pork belly.

298
00:11:47,106 --> 00:11:49,008
This is another pack of beef.

299
00:11:49,075 --> 00:11:52,511
-I'm starting to see some meat.
-That looks like beef too.

300
00:11:52,578 --> 00:11:54,213
I keep seeing more meat.

301
00:11:54,280 --> 00:11:57,717
I really love meat,
so I eat about 1 kg in a meal.

302
00:11:57,783 --> 00:11:59,218
-One kilogram?
-Yes.

303
00:11:59,285 --> 00:12:02,822
He'll have to order ten servings
when he goes out to eat.

304
00:12:02,888 --> 00:12:04,557
On the day
when we met for the first time,

305
00:12:04,623 --> 00:12:08,027
he had about 1.3 kg of steak
all by himself.

306
00:12:08,094 --> 00:12:11,664
-He had two servings of porterhouse steak.
-Two?

307
00:12:11,731 --> 00:12:14,100
That's a big size.

308
00:12:14,166 --> 00:12:16,001
-He's like a lion.
-Yes.

309
00:12:16,068 --> 00:12:18,604
I see lots of veggies too.
Do you enjoy them?

310
00:12:18,671 --> 00:12:21,941
-I don't like vegetables.
-Do you not eat these?

311
00:12:22,007 --> 00:12:23,876
My wife loves them.

312
00:12:23,943 --> 00:12:26,979
She always juices vegetables
every single morning

313
00:12:27,046 --> 00:12:30,883
<i>-and drinks it.</i>
<i>-Like vegetable juice.</i>

314
00:12:30,950 --> 00:12:32,384
Do you not like perilla leaves?

315
00:12:32,451 --> 00:12:35,387
-I do like those. I love perilla leaves.
-You do?

316
00:12:35,454 --> 00:12:39,892
-Is this <i>shiso</i>?
-Yes, I like how they have that smell.

317
00:12:39,959 --> 00:12:41,694
That's why I like those.

318
00:12:41,761 --> 00:12:43,596
Are <i>shiso</i> and perilla leaves
very different?

319
00:12:43,662 --> 00:12:45,264
They look similar,

320
00:12:45,331 --> 00:12:48,300
but <i>shiso </i>is a bit more minty.

321
00:12:48,367 --> 00:12:51,403
-It's really good. Basil or mint.
-It's like basil of Japan.

322
00:12:51,470 --> 00:12:53,305
How about pumpkins and carrots?

323
00:12:53,372 --> 00:12:54,707
Pumpkins and carrots?

324
00:12:57,243 --> 00:12:58,878
-You don't enjoy those too much.
-No.

325
00:12:58,944 --> 00:13:00,579
-Not too many pumpkins and carrots.
-No.

326
00:13:00,646 --> 00:13:03,549
I found some seafood. Gosh.

327
00:13:03,616 --> 00:13:06,085
-These look like fish.
-Yes, those are fish.

328
00:13:06,152 --> 00:13:08,220
-Blackthroat seaperch.
-Blackthroat seaperch?

329
00:13:08,287 --> 00:13:09,321
Do you like chocolate?

330
00:13:09,388 --> 00:13:12,625
I saw that you seemed to love dessert
on your YouTube channel.

331
00:13:12,691 --> 00:13:14,360
-I do love desserts.
-You do?

332
00:13:14,426 --> 00:13:18,564
I do. I go around
hunting for good dessert places.

333
00:13:18,631 --> 00:13:21,400
At times, Sa-rang will gather her friends

334
00:13:21,467 --> 00:13:23,803
and bake cookies for me.

335
00:13:23,869 --> 00:13:26,605
I like to enjoy those with her.

336
00:13:26,672 --> 00:13:28,207
-I see.
-I like it.

337
00:13:28,274 --> 00:13:30,509
As an Italian chef,

338
00:13:30,576 --> 00:13:32,711
I want to know if he has cheese.

339
00:13:33,279 --> 00:13:35,414
-Cheese?
-I thought I had some.

340
00:13:35,481 --> 00:13:36,849
-No?
-Does he have cheese?

341
00:13:36,916 --> 00:13:39,084
SUNG-HOON HAD SOME CHEESE

342
00:13:39,151 --> 00:13:41,887
EXCITED

343
00:13:41,954 --> 00:13:45,157
-He had cheese.
-That's cheese.

344
00:13:45,224 --> 00:13:47,059
I found this too.

345
00:13:47,126 --> 00:13:48,627
-He has lots of butters.
-He does.

346
00:13:48,694 --> 00:13:51,997
-Those look luxurious.
-These are butters too.

347
00:13:52,064 --> 00:13:53,699
-What's that?
-What is that?

348
00:13:53,766 --> 00:13:56,335
-Ravioli?
-Pasta, I think.

349
00:13:56,402 --> 00:13:57,469
Do you enjoy pasta?

350
00:13:57,536 --> 00:13:59,138
-Yes.
-But it's ready-made.

351
00:13:59,205 --> 00:14:00,806
He can take the easy way and use those.

352
00:14:00,873 --> 00:14:03,142
-They can't do that.
-They can't.

353
00:14:03,209 --> 00:14:04,443
And room temperature ingredients.

354
00:14:05,211 --> 00:14:07,313
I'm seeing lots of noodles.

355
00:14:07,379 --> 00:14:09,415
-Pasta.
-Yes, spaghetti.

356
00:14:09,481 --> 00:14:12,284
-Noodles.
-He really loves noodles.

357
00:14:12,351 --> 00:14:14,820
I do like noodles.

358
00:14:14,887 --> 00:14:18,257
I'm not in season right now,

359
00:14:18,324 --> 00:14:20,426
so I eat carbs once a week.

360
00:14:20,492 --> 00:14:21,861
-Once a week?
-The thing is,

361
00:14:21,927 --> 00:14:23,963
today is that day.

362
00:14:24,029 --> 00:14:25,798
So you don't have to worry about that.

363
00:14:26,398 --> 00:14:28,500
That was all for Sung-hoon's fridge.

364
00:14:28,567 --> 00:14:31,303
WE'RE DONE
LOOKING THROUGH SUNG-HOON'S FRIDGE!

365
00:14:31,370 --> 00:14:35,174
And now, let's find out
Sung-hoon's orders.

366
00:14:35,241 --> 00:14:36,242
Please show us.

367
00:14:36,308 --> 00:14:39,278
-The first one. Sexy food.
-Sexy food.

368
00:14:39,345 --> 00:14:40,512
And carbohydrates.

369
00:14:41,480 --> 00:14:43,849
And you named the order "sexy food"

370
00:14:43,916 --> 00:14:48,020
-because you're nicknamed Sexy Yama.
-Yes.

371
00:14:48,087 --> 00:14:50,189
And "sexy food" is the newest buzzword.

372
00:14:50,256 --> 00:14:54,393
-Apparently so.
-Yes, kids use it to describe good food.

373
00:14:54,460 --> 00:14:57,096
-They call it sexy food.
-Is that so? I see.

374
00:14:57,162 --> 00:14:58,831
What do you mean by this?

375
00:14:58,898 --> 00:15:02,701
As I mentioned before,
I only eat carbs once a week.

376
00:15:02,768 --> 00:15:06,805
So with every chance I get in a week,
I always want to eat something good.

377
00:15:06,872 --> 00:15:09,708
I wanted to ask the chefs
to make something here.

378
00:15:09,775 --> 00:15:10,776
I'd be very grateful.

379
00:15:10,843 --> 00:15:12,177
-I see.
-It's your carb day.

380
00:15:12,244 --> 00:15:15,247
Yes, it's my carb day.

381
00:15:15,314 --> 00:15:17,149
What's Sung-hoon's second order?

382
00:15:17,216 --> 00:15:19,218
What does he want to eat?

383
00:15:19,285 --> 00:15:22,554
Sexy Food: Protein.

384
00:15:22,621 --> 00:15:27,026
I'm an athlete,
so protein intake is important to me.

385
00:15:27,092 --> 00:15:29,728
I really love to eat meat,

386
00:15:29,795 --> 00:15:33,299
so I want to eat something very delicious.
I eat a lot of meat,

387
00:15:33,365 --> 00:15:36,902
-so I know when it's delicious or not.
-You'd know.

388
00:15:36,969 --> 00:15:39,004
-This is hard.
-Please do that for me.

389
00:15:39,071 --> 00:15:41,206
You have to make it really good.

390
00:15:41,273 --> 00:15:44,543
If it's not good,
I'll give you a serious low kick.

391
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:46,412
-This is bad.
-A low kick?

392
00:15:46,478 --> 00:15:49,048
He'll give you a low kick
if it's not delicious.

393
00:15:49,114 --> 00:15:51,517
It'll hurt a lot.

394
00:15:51,583 --> 00:15:53,519
Two chefs remain

395
00:15:53,585 --> 00:15:56,989
among the four top Asian chefs,
Chef Yusuke and Chef Antimo.

396
00:15:57,056 --> 00:15:59,158
So there are two rounds remaining,

397
00:15:59,224 --> 00:16:01,627
so two of you will be benched.

398
00:16:03,696 --> 00:16:06,065
I'll give Chef Yusuke the first choice.

399
00:16:06,131 --> 00:16:08,600
Please pick your order and opponent.

400
00:16:08,667 --> 00:16:10,402
-Make your decision.
-I want to fight him.

401
00:16:10,469 --> 00:16:13,973
-Protein.
-Protein. The order for protein.

402
00:16:14,039 --> 00:16:16,775
He's going with the meat.

403
00:16:16,842 --> 00:16:18,677
That was a great choice.

404
00:16:18,744 --> 00:16:20,179
He runs
the eighth best restaurant in Asia.

405
00:16:20,245 --> 00:16:23,182
-Who do you want to fight?
-Please.

406
00:16:23,248 --> 00:16:25,317
-Jong-won, Nam-no,
-This won't be easy.

407
00:16:25,384 --> 00:16:26,952
Sung-jun, and even Fabri.

408
00:16:27,019 --> 00:16:28,654
Who will you fight, Chef Yusuke?

409
00:16:28,721 --> 00:16:30,656
Will it be Nam-no?

410
00:16:30,723 --> 00:16:31,924
The good-looking Chef Jong-won.

411
00:16:33,525 --> 00:16:34,994
How disappointing.

412
00:16:38,197 --> 00:16:39,865
"We both made it into the top 50,

413
00:16:39,932 --> 00:16:43,035
-but I was the 8th, you were the 25th."
-Yes.

414
00:16:43,102 --> 00:16:46,438
-"Feel the difference."
-Find out how big the difference is.

415
00:16:46,505 --> 00:16:47,906
-"Feel it, Jong-won."
-Yes.

416
00:16:47,973 --> 00:16:52,077
Chef Antimo, you'll automatically
have to go with carbs.

417
00:16:54,113 --> 00:16:55,981
But you can choose your opponent.

418
00:16:56,048 --> 00:16:58,650
Sung-jun, Nam-no, or Fabri.

419
00:16:59,885 --> 00:17:01,720
What?

420
00:17:01,787 --> 00:17:05,424
-The other Italian chef.
-The fake Neapolitan.

421
00:17:05,491 --> 00:17:06,625
The fake one.

422
00:17:06,692 --> 00:17:08,694
In that case, okay.

423
00:17:08,761 --> 00:17:11,430
Today will be a true Italian battle.

424
00:17:12,598 --> 00:17:13,665
Is that how you'll take it?

425
00:17:13,732 --> 00:17:16,402
The fake Italian is out,
so the two Italians are in this fight.

426
00:17:17,703 --> 00:17:18,704
It'll be a good game.

427
00:17:19,271 --> 00:17:20,873
COMING RIGHT UP!

428
00:17:20,939 --> 00:17:22,508
I'm really nervous.

429
00:17:22,574 --> 00:17:23,909
How sexy!

430
00:17:23,976 --> 00:17:26,311
ONE BEAST IS HERE

431
00:17:26,378 --> 00:17:28,580
-This is crazy.
-How crazy!

432
00:17:28,647 --> 00:17:30,115
TO MAKE THE TOP ASIAN CHEFS NERVOUS

433
00:17:32,951 --> 00:17:35,854
-Will you chew a little?
-I think he's just swallowing it.

434
00:17:35,921 --> 00:17:37,523
It doesn't feel real.

435
00:17:37,589 --> 00:17:38,757
HE REFUSES ALL VEGGIES!

436
00:17:38,824 --> 00:17:40,025
He destroyed it.

437
00:17:40,092 --> 00:17:41,360
Wait!

438
00:17:41,427 --> 00:17:43,695
-It's destroyed.
-He chopped it into two.

439
00:17:43,762 --> 00:17:45,164
He licked the knife.

440
00:17:45,230 --> 00:17:47,099
THE BEAST'S MUKBANG, COMING SOON…

441
00:17:47,166 --> 00:17:51,370
<i>You're now watching</i>
<i>the Big Asian Competition.</i>

442
00:17:51,437 --> 00:17:55,941
This is the first round
using Sung-hoon's ingredients.

443
00:17:56,008 --> 00:17:59,144
We already had two rounds last week.

444
00:17:59,211 --> 00:18:02,481
<i>Top Asian chefs</i>
<i>versus the cast of</i> Chef & My Fridge.

445
00:18:02,548 --> 00:18:05,117
We ended in a tie last week
with a score of one to one.

446
00:18:05,184 --> 00:18:08,020
And now, we're about to begin
two more rounds.

447
00:18:08,087 --> 00:18:10,989
Napoli Matfia, Chef Kwon Sung-jun, is

448
00:18:11,056 --> 00:18:16,128
up against the 32nd place
of Asia's 50 Best Restaurants,

449
00:18:16,195 --> 00:18:20,132
the real Neapolitan, Chef Antimo,
a so-called Naples death match.

450
00:18:20,199 --> 00:18:22,901
And we have one Milanese watching.

451
00:18:22,968 --> 00:18:25,537
Chef Fabri is Milanese,

452
00:18:25,604 --> 00:18:28,207
so I wasn't too nervous when I fought him.

453
00:18:28,273 --> 00:18:29,408
But today,

454
00:18:29,475 --> 00:18:34,480
I'll fight a true Neapolitan to convey
the true essence of Italian cuisine.

455
00:18:34,546 --> 00:18:35,881
So I'm a bit nervous today.

456
00:18:35,948 --> 00:18:39,485
Chef Antimo, how long
did you live in Naples?

457
00:18:42,654 --> 00:18:45,858
-Until 19.
-He spent his childhood there.

458
00:18:45,924 --> 00:18:47,993
I lived there until I was 26.

459
00:18:48,060 --> 00:18:50,429
-From when?
-From when?

460
00:18:50,496 --> 00:18:51,964
From when I was 25.

461
00:18:53,365 --> 00:18:56,301
-A year?
-A year? A year and a half?

462
00:18:56,368 --> 00:18:58,203
These two chefs

463
00:18:58,270 --> 00:19:01,006
-went to the same school.
-What?

464
00:19:01,073 --> 00:19:05,611
They both attended
Alma Culinary School in Italy.

465
00:19:05,677 --> 00:19:07,146
For your information,

466
00:19:07,212 --> 00:19:09,982
Chef Antimo graduated
at the top of his class.

467
00:19:10,048 --> 00:19:11,783
-Really?
-Yes.

468
00:19:11,850 --> 00:19:15,821
I was the judge for their exit exam.

469
00:19:15,888 --> 00:19:17,556
You were the judge for Alma?

470
00:19:17,623 --> 00:19:19,091
-Not the student.
-Not the student.

471
00:19:19,158 --> 00:19:22,828
-You were on the level of a professor.
-Yes, of course.

472
00:19:22,895 --> 00:19:24,263
REALIZING FABRI'S INFLUENCE ONCE AGAIN

473
00:19:24,329 --> 00:19:26,431
Wait, so Sung-jun didn't work there?

474
00:19:26,498 --> 00:19:27,599
He went to school.

475
00:19:27,666 --> 00:19:29,801
-I worked there too.
-You did?

476
00:19:29,868 --> 00:19:31,436
-I worked and studied.
-At Alma?

477
00:19:31,503 --> 00:19:34,039
How long was the course?

478
00:19:34,106 --> 00:19:37,342
-The school? Three months.
-Three months?

479
00:19:37,409 --> 00:19:38,810
-Three months?
-Three?

480
00:19:38,877 --> 00:19:41,280
There is a three-month course.

481
00:19:41,346 --> 00:19:44,116
-That sounds like a trip.
-A trip?

482
00:19:44,183 --> 00:19:46,685
That makes me an Italian too.
I was there for three years.

483
00:19:46,752 --> 00:19:47,853
Yes, three years.

484
00:19:47,920 --> 00:19:49,421
You were there much longer.

485
00:19:49,488 --> 00:19:52,191
I played there for three years.

486
00:19:52,257 --> 00:19:54,126
Yes, right. In Serie A.

487
00:19:54,193 --> 00:19:55,594
