Press two for Chef Kwon Sung-jun.

977
00:42:15,165 --> 00:42:18,869
-Which carb dish did you like better?
-This is a tough one.

978
00:42:18,936 --> 00:42:20,971
Please press the button.

979
00:42:21,038 --> 00:42:23,240
He finally had carbs
for the first time in a while.

980
00:42:24,408 --> 00:42:26,710
It's taking him a while.

981
00:42:26,777 --> 00:42:29,113
-He rarely hesitates like this.
-No.

982
00:42:29,179 --> 00:42:30,948
He's usually very decisive.

983
00:42:31,015 --> 00:42:33,851
-I pressed one.
-He did.

984
00:42:33,918 --> 00:42:35,886
Let's find out who the winner is.

985
00:42:35,953 --> 00:42:37,354
Which one of them won?

986
00:42:37,421 --> 00:42:40,858
That was Sexy Food: Carbohydrate round.

987
00:42:40,925 --> 00:42:44,261
Will it be Kwon Sung-jun,
the winner of <i>Culinary Class Wars</i>?

988
00:42:44,328 --> 00:42:47,631
Or will it be Antimo, who made it
into Asia's 50 Best Restaurants?

989
00:42:47,698 --> 00:42:50,167
Who did Sung-hoon choose?

990
00:42:50,701 --> 00:42:53,237
Who's the winner?

991
00:42:55,439 --> 00:42:57,374
CHEF ANTIMO'S NAPOLI POLIZIA

992
00:42:57,441 --> 00:42:58,442
Chef Antimo!

993
00:42:59,643 --> 00:43:01,412
Chef Antimo wins.

994
00:43:03,080 --> 00:43:05,382
Please have a seat.

995
00:43:05,449 --> 00:43:07,818
-Let's hear from him.
-Thank you.

996
00:43:07,885 --> 00:43:12,389
He boiled the pasta
for about 5 minutes and 30 seconds.

997
00:43:12,456 --> 00:43:16,427
And he could do that in five minutes
because he used hot water for the dough.

998
00:43:16,493 --> 00:43:17,728
That was new to me,

999
00:43:17,795 --> 00:43:20,030
and also, the sauce was excellent.

1000
00:43:20,097 --> 00:43:21,365
It was so creamy,

1001
00:43:21,432 --> 00:43:25,035
a flavor that even babies would enjoy.

1002
00:43:25,102 --> 00:43:27,237
I finally had
a chance to eat carbs after a while,

1003
00:43:27,304 --> 00:43:29,340
so I enjoyed it and was even touched.

1004
00:43:29,406 --> 00:43:32,209
-I see.
-Phew.

1005
00:43:33,811 --> 00:43:37,381
-He's wiping sweat off his forehead.
-Yes.

1006
00:43:37,448 --> 00:43:39,617
Can you tell us how you feel?

1007
00:43:47,291 --> 00:43:50,494
Yes, please put a star on him.

1008
00:43:50,561 --> 00:43:52,496
The Naples round is over.

1009
00:43:52,563 --> 00:43:54,465
There's my second star.

1010
00:43:54,531 --> 00:43:58,102
Congratulations for the star, Chef Antimo!

1011
00:43:58,836 --> 00:44:02,473
-He's the winner of the Naples round.
-Bravo. Congratulations.

1012
00:44:02,539 --> 00:44:07,011
<i>This is the Big Asian Competition</i>
<i>held with Sung-hoon's ingredients.</i>

1013
00:44:07,077 --> 00:44:08,812
<i>This is the finale.</i>

1014
00:44:08,879 --> 00:44:10,781
From Japan, Chef Takada Yusuke.

1015
00:44:10,848 --> 00:44:14,084
From Korea, Chef Son Jong-won.

1016
00:44:14,151 --> 00:44:17,788
<i>This round is between</i>
<i>the 8th and 25th places among the 50.</i>

1017
00:44:18,389 --> 00:44:22,793
Chef Yusuke maintained his two stars
in the Michelin Guide for ten years.

1018
00:44:22,860 --> 00:44:23,861
Gosh.

1019
00:44:23,927 --> 00:44:29,199
But Chef Jong-won is the only Korean chef
who has two one-star restaurants.

1020
00:44:29,266 --> 00:44:32,002
I believe this will be
a round to remember.

1021
00:44:32,069 --> 00:44:33,604
-It's the biggest match.
-The Korea-Japan round.

1022
00:44:33,671 --> 00:44:35,472
-That's right.
-The biggest match.

1023
00:44:35,539 --> 00:44:38,742
We say we must win in rock-paper-scissors
if it's a Korea-Japan round.

1024
00:44:38,809 --> 00:44:40,544
-So much pressure.
-Chef Jong-won.

1025
00:44:40,611 --> 00:44:42,413
Do you feel that pressure?

1026
00:44:42,479 --> 00:44:44,682
-There's a lot of pressure.
-I see.

1027
00:44:44,748 --> 00:44:46,984
Chef Yusuke, do you feel the pressure too?

1028
00:44:47,051 --> 00:44:49,653
I'm conscious about it. I'll do my best.

1029
00:44:50,220 --> 00:44:52,222
THE TENSION IS ALREADY HIGH

1030
00:44:52,289 --> 00:44:55,459
But you know,
the situation is kind of funny.

1031
00:44:55,526 --> 00:44:58,696
-Sung-hoon mostly had Japanese food.
-Yes.

1032
00:44:58,762 --> 00:45:00,764
He's also from Osaka,

1033
00:45:00,831 --> 00:45:03,767
and Chef Yusuke has his restaurant there.

1034
00:45:03,834 --> 00:45:05,469
ARE THE ODDS AGAINST JONG-WON?

1035
00:45:05,536 --> 00:45:07,971
-It's like a home match for Chef Yusuke.
-Yes.

1036
00:45:08,038 --> 00:45:09,907
I thought I'd have the upper hand,

1037
00:45:09,973 --> 00:45:10,974
but the ingredients

1038
00:45:11,041 --> 00:45:14,144
didn't make me seem
too much at home, so I was surprised.

1039
00:45:14,211 --> 00:45:16,580
-But this show is my home ground.
-Yes.

1040
00:45:16,647 --> 00:45:18,148
I'll do my best within 15 minutes.

1041
00:45:18,215 --> 00:45:20,117
He talks that gentle,

1042
00:45:20,184 --> 00:45:23,454
but we recorded something
when he was in the green room.

1043
00:45:23,520 --> 00:45:25,889
Someone asked,
"Can you win against the eighth place?"

1044
00:45:25,956 --> 00:45:27,725
He said, "Michelin stars

1045
00:45:27,791 --> 00:45:29,927
and the top 50 restaurants in Asia

1046
00:45:29,993 --> 00:45:32,129
are both meaningless

1047
00:45:32,196 --> 00:45:33,464
before the 15-minute time limit."

1048
00:45:35,499 --> 00:45:37,968
IT'S TIME TO PROVOKE HIM

1049
00:45:38,569 --> 00:45:40,003
HURT

1050
00:45:40,070 --> 00:45:42,606
-"Michelin star? Whatever."
-He doesn't need it.

1051
00:45:42,673 --> 00:45:45,375
"Who cares about the top 50
or the 8th place?"

1052
00:45:45,442 --> 00:45:47,277
-That's right.
-Yes.

1053
00:45:47,344 --> 00:45:50,114
He means that
it's hard to cook in 15 minutes.

1054
00:45:50,180 --> 00:45:52,249
-It is. It's very hard.
-Yes.

1055
00:45:52,316 --> 00:45:53,751
I'm very nervous.

1056
00:45:55,219 --> 00:45:58,322
Do you regret your decision
to appear on the show?

1057
00:45:58,388 --> 00:45:59,723
A little.

1058
00:46:00,824 --> 00:46:03,861
-He's regretting it a little.
-He regrets it a little.

1059
00:46:03,927 --> 00:46:05,829
It's because it's finally his turn.

1060
00:46:05,896 --> 00:46:07,564
The same rule applies.

1061
00:46:07,631 --> 00:46:11,635
-Chef Yusuke can use a perk.
-Of course.

1062
00:46:11,702 --> 00:46:14,872
-I have a feeling he'll use it.
-People from Osaka won't do it.

1063
00:46:14,938 --> 00:46:16,774
-Will you use it?
-People from Osaka won't do it.

1064
00:46:16,840 --> 00:46:20,110
-Will you use it?
-People from Osaka won't do it.

1065
00:46:21,078 --> 00:46:22,546
-I won't use it.
-What?

1066
00:46:22,613 --> 00:46:24,715
-I won't use it.
-What?

1067
00:46:24,782 --> 00:46:26,784
It was just as he said.

1068
00:46:26,850 --> 00:46:29,386
THE CHEFS WHO HAVE BEEN THERE
SHOWS HIM RESPECT

1069
00:46:29,453 --> 00:46:33,390
People from Osaka have
a very strong pride.

1070
00:46:35,859 --> 00:46:38,529
CHEF YUSUKE'S INGREDIENTS: NOODLES, SHISO,
ACAI BERRY SMOOTHIE, TENDERLOIN STEAK

1071
00:46:38,595 --> 00:46:41,198
SUKIYAKI MEAT, PERILLA LEAF, YOGURT,
TRIPLE BERRIES, RED BEAN PASTE, AND MORE

1072
00:46:41,265 --> 00:46:44,268
Chef Yusuke, what are you making?

1073
00:46:44,334 --> 00:46:48,105
-It's called Takada-licious.
-Takada-licious.

1074
00:46:48,172 --> 00:46:49,640
That's your surname.

1075
00:46:49,706 --> 00:46:51,542
-Itadakimasu.
-"Thanks for the delicious food."

1076
00:46:51,608 --> 00:46:53,443
It's a phrase Japanese people say
before they eat.

1077
00:46:54,011 --> 00:46:56,814
A CUTE WORDPLAY WITH HIS SURNAME

1078
00:46:57,381 --> 00:46:58,515
He mixed in his name.

1079
00:46:58,582 --> 00:47:00,617
-That's funny.
-Takada-licious.

1080
00:47:00,684 --> 00:47:05,889
I heard Sung-hoon likes meat,

1081
00:47:05,956 --> 00:47:08,392
so first, I'll grill steak.

1082
00:47:08,458 --> 00:47:10,694
I'll also make some noodles
by using bone broth.

1083
00:47:10,761 --> 00:47:12,863
-I see.
-It's like the thin noodles.

1084
00:47:12,930 --> 00:47:15,632
I'll use cream, yogurt,

1085
00:47:15,699 --> 00:47:18,735
and the smoothie in the fridge
to make some dessert too.

1086
00:47:18,802 --> 00:47:21,205
HE'LL MAKE 3 DIFFERENT DISHES

1087
00:47:21,271 --> 00:47:22,339
That's amazing.

1088
00:47:23,073 --> 00:47:25,776
CHEF JONG-WON'S INGREDIENTS: HONEY, BREAD,
JAPANESE PICKLED CUCUMBER, CRUSHED GARLIC

1089
00:47:25,843 --> 00:47:28,579
PLAIN YOGURT, SHISO, LEMON, STEAK SAUCE,
ORGANIC MILK, TOFU, TENDERLOIN, AND MORE

1090
00:47:28,645 --> 00:47:29,813
I prepared

1091
00:47:29,880 --> 00:47:32,349
Choo-rotein Sweep.

1092
00:47:32,416 --> 00:47:33,684
-Choo?
-Choo-rotein.

1093
00:47:33,750 --> 00:47:35,319
-Protein and Choo.
-Yes.

1094
00:47:35,385 --> 00:47:38,689
I'll use the protein ingredients
in Sung-hoon's fridge

1095
00:47:38,755 --> 00:47:40,924
to make a three-course meal
you can sweep into your mouth.

1096
00:47:40,991 --> 00:47:43,093
HE PREPARED 3 DISHES TOO

1097
00:47:43,160 --> 00:47:47,631
-He's making three dishes too.
-That's a lot.

1098
00:47:47,698 --> 00:47:50,067
What kind of a dish will it be?

1099
00:47:50,133 --> 00:47:53,871
I'll use eel and avocado to make a toast.

1100
00:47:53,937 --> 00:47:56,139
I'll also grill some steak

1101
00:47:56,206 --> 00:47:57,708
and use some veggies with it too.

1102
00:47:57,774 --> 00:48:00,878
Lastly, I'll make the dessert
with soft tofu.

1103
00:48:02,346 --> 00:48:05,115
-Can he do that in 15 minutes?
-I wonder.

1104
00:48:05,182 --> 00:48:07,050
But he's going to try.

1105
00:48:07,117 --> 00:48:09,786
One of them is from Osaka, just like you.

1106
00:48:09,853 --> 00:48:12,856
And you kicked the other one.

1107
00:48:12,923 --> 00:48:14,958
-Only at 25%.
-Yes.

1108
00:48:15,025 --> 00:48:18,095
This is the long-awaited final round

1109
00:48:18,161 --> 00:48:20,597
of the Big Asian Competition.

1110
00:48:20,664 --> 00:48:22,833
Let's begin the Korea-Japan round.

1111
00:48:23,967 --> 00:48:26,837
He's here to show his class
as the 8th place among 50,

1112
00:48:26,904 --> 00:48:30,574
a two-star Michelin chef from Japan,
Takada Yusuke.

1113
00:48:30,641 --> 00:48:33,310
The handsomest chef in Asia,

1114
00:48:33,377 --> 00:48:36,914
a double-star Michelin chef in Korea,
Son Jong-won is up against him.

1115
00:48:36,980 --> 00:48:41,685
Who'll capture Sexy Yama's appetite
and win the Korea-Japan round?

1116
00:48:41,752 --> 00:48:44,488
Let the 15-minute cook-off begin!

1117
00:48:47,190 --> 00:48:50,961
THE FINAL ROUND BEGINS!

1118
00:48:51,028 --> 00:48:52,162
Begin!

1119
00:48:52,229 --> 00:48:53,530
JONG-WON RUSHES OUT

1120
00:48:55,032 --> 00:48:56,166
Hey, that's an eel.

1121
00:48:56,233 --> 00:48:57,301
Hey, it's an eel.

1122
00:48:57,367 --> 00:48:58,835
You had seasoned eels?

1123
00:48:58,902 --> 00:49:01,805
Yes, I always had it.

1124
00:49:01,872 --> 00:49:04,574
Chef Yusuke uses the bone broth.

1125
00:49:04,641 --> 00:49:06,043
-Is it bone broth?
-Yes.

1126
00:49:06,109 --> 00:49:07,911
1. ADD SMALL ANCHOVIES
TO BONE BROTH AND BOIL

1127
00:49:07,978 --> 00:49:11,281
These top Asian chefs
don't seem to be nervous.

1128
00:49:11,348 --> 00:49:12,916
He seems too relaxed.

1129
00:49:12,983 --> 00:49:15,118
-He's very calm.
-He is.

1130
00:49:15,185 --> 00:49:18,956
As we speak, both sides began to use meat.

1131
00:49:19,022 --> 00:49:20,357
-Is that tenderloin?
-No.

1132
00:49:20,424 --> 00:49:23,827
Chef Jong-won ties a thread
around the meat before he grills it.

1133
00:49:23,894 --> 00:49:26,797
He wants to keep
the same thick medal shape.

1134
00:49:26,863 --> 00:49:28,532
-To make sure it doesn't go flat?
-Right.

1135
00:49:28,598 --> 00:49:30,267
Hey, already?

1136
00:49:30,334 --> 00:49:32,369
Chef Yusuke begins to grill his meat.

1137
00:49:32,436 --> 00:49:35,539
-He's using oil and butter.
-Butter? I see.

1138
00:49:35,605 --> 00:49:37,107
He's cooking it over low heat.

1139
00:49:37,174 --> 00:49:39,543
Yes, Chef Jong-won tied up the meat.

1140
00:49:39,609 --> 00:49:43,714
That'll keep the meat quite thick,
so he'll need techniques to cook that.

1141
00:49:43,780 --> 00:49:46,183
It must be hard.
He'll need some techniques.

1142
00:49:46,249 --> 00:49:48,752
He seared both sides first.

1143
00:49:48,819 --> 00:49:50,754
That's why he begins with the steak.

1144
00:49:52,823 --> 00:49:54,624
Chef Yusuke seems at ease.

1145
00:49:54,691 --> 00:49:59,196
He moves smoothly yet steadily like water.

1146
00:49:59,262 --> 00:50:01,732
-Very steadily.
-Quietly.

1147
00:50:02,265 --> 00:50:05,569
He flips the steak just once.

1148
00:50:06,603 --> 00:50:08,071
Now, he's already…

1149
00:50:08,138 --> 00:50:09,673
What are those? Cilantro?

1150
00:50:09,740 --> 00:50:10,741
-What are those?
-Arugula?

1151
00:50:10,807 --> 00:50:12,042
I don't think so.

1152
00:50:12,109 --> 00:50:13,543
Are those arugula?

1153
00:50:14,378 --> 00:50:15,579
-What are those?
-Kale.

1154
00:50:15,645 --> 00:50:18,615
-Kale.
-Kale? Baby kale.

1155
00:50:18,682 --> 00:50:22,886
-The kale his wife juices.
-The baby kale.

1156
00:50:22,953 --> 00:50:26,089
The kale his wife juices.
He has a new way of cooking steak.

1157
00:50:26,156 --> 00:50:28,091
Why does he do that?
Does he need the smell?

1158
00:50:28,158 --> 00:50:31,928
It'll add a lot of juice
and make the meat tender.

1159
00:50:31,995 --> 00:50:33,830
He's trying to make the steak tender.

1160
00:50:34,998 --> 00:50:37,234
Chef Yusuke uses cherry tomatoes.

1161
00:50:37,300 --> 00:50:38,602
Yes.

1162
00:50:38,668 --> 00:50:39,803
HE CUTS ONE

1163
00:50:40,437 --> 00:50:41,338
AND CHECKS

1164
00:50:41,405 --> 00:50:42,572
ANOTHER ONE

1165
00:50:42,639 --> 00:50:43,807
AND CHECKS AGAIN

1166
00:50:44,441 --> 00:50:48,045
HE'S VERY METICULOUS
AT GETTING THE TOMATOES READY

1167
00:50:48,111 --> 00:50:50,414
I think he'll run out of time.

1168
00:50:50,480 --> 00:50:53,650
-The master has everything planned out.
-He has to cook three dishes.

1169
00:50:54,918 --> 00:50:56,486
DONE WITH THE TOMATOES

1170
00:50:56,553 --> 00:50:58,822
-Bread.
-Chef Yusuke.

1171
00:50:59,890 --> 00:51:01,525
He grabbed some bread.

1172
00:51:02,192 --> 00:51:04,828
HE FLATTENS THE BREAD

1173
00:51:04,895 --> 00:51:06,730
What's the round thing
Chef Jong-won is using?

1174
00:51:06,797 --> 00:51:08,899
-It's bread.
-It's bread.

1175
00:51:08,965 --> 00:51:12,669
He once made tart shells by using bread.

1176
00:51:13,403 --> 00:51:15,439
NEXT, BUTTER!

1177
00:51:16,273 --> 00:51:17,741
METICULOUS

1178
00:51:17,808 --> 00:51:21,545
3. BUTTER ROUND-SHAPED BREAD
AND ROAST IN THE OVEN

1179
00:51:21,611 --> 00:51:23,880
GO IN WITH THE EEL

1180
00:51:23,947 --> 00:51:27,484
THE MEAT IS STILL RESTING

1181
00:51:27,551 --> 00:51:29,719
BUTTER

1182
00:51:29,786 --> 00:51:31,555
Whoa, look at the amount of butter.

1183
00:51:31,621 --> 00:51:32,989
He's putting in ippai.

1184
00:51:33,056 --> 00:51:34,624
"Ippai"?

1185
00:51:34,691 --> 00:51:36,359
-Excuse me.
-The meat looks similar…

1186
00:51:36,426 --> 00:51:37,661
Since there are Japanese people here.

1187
00:51:37,727 --> 00:51:40,497
Whoa, look at him go with butter.

1188
00:51:40,564 --> 00:51:44,568
Meat and butter are probably the best mix.

1189
00:51:44,634 --> 00:51:48,338
Chef Yusuke put the butter in the pan,
but Chef Jong-won showers the meat.

1190
00:51:48,405 --> 00:51:49,406
CHECKING FOR THE TEMPERATURE

1191
00:51:49,473 --> 00:51:52,542
-So sexy.
-Yes, that was sexy.

1192
00:51:52,609 --> 00:51:55,445
Anyway, this is the protein round,

1193
00:51:55,512 --> 00:51:58,448
-so the meat needs to look good.
-Right.

1194
00:51:58,515 --> 00:51:59,950
Is he resting the meat?

1195
00:52:00,016 --> 00:52:01,485
Yes, he's resting it.

1196
00:52:01,551 --> 00:52:05,055
3. COVER TENDERLOIN WITH FOIL
AND LET IT REST

1197
00:52:06,256 --> 00:52:08,058
He's using two kinds of meat.

1198
00:52:08,125 --> 00:52:10,927
-That's another meat?
-You picked out another meat?

1199
00:52:10,994 --> 00:52:13,864
Soy sauce. This time,
he's seasoning meat with soy sauce.

1200
00:52:13,930 --> 00:52:17,934
He's grilling another piece of meat,
so these will sit in soy sauce.

1201
00:52:18,001 --> 00:52:19,236
AND?

1202
00:52:19,302 --> 00:52:21,271
I see. The yeast with salt.

1203
00:52:21,338 --> 00:52:22,672
This is a wonder.

1204
00:52:22,739 --> 00:52:26,476
He's mixing that yeast with salt
with the meat.

1205
00:52:26,543 --> 00:52:29,312
It's probably to tenderize the meat.

1206
00:52:29,379 --> 00:52:30,747
I see.

1207
00:52:30,814 --> 00:52:32,516
-That's how people use it.
-Come on.

1208
00:52:32,582 --> 00:52:34,451
-He's using more broth.
-The broth.

1209
00:52:34,518 --> 00:52:38,021
In the end,
he opened up another pack of broth.

1210
00:52:38,922 --> 00:52:42,959
He's boiling the seasoned meat in that.

1211
00:52:43,026 --> 00:52:45,562
He said he'd make thin noodles with that.

1212
00:52:46,830 --> 00:52:48,265
He threw the noodles in.

1213
00:52:48,331 --> 00:52:51,201
-He did?
-He put it in right here.

1214
00:52:51,268 --> 00:52:53,803
-Why are they both so composed?
-Right?

1215
00:52:53,870 --> 00:52:55,672
I'm nervous.

1216
00:52:55,739 --> 00:52:57,374
They seem composed,

1217
00:52:57,440 --> 00:53:00,911
-but Chef Jong-won seems a bit faster.
-He's a bit faster.

1218
00:53:00,977 --> 00:53:03,446
Can he make dessert so quickly?

1219
00:53:03,513 --> 00:53:05,382
Can they both make three dishes in time?

1220
00:53:05,448 --> 00:53:07,517
5. BOIL MILK, BLACK TEA BAG,
AND SUGAR TO MAKE MILK TEA

1221
00:53:09,853 --> 00:53:11,388
Hey, that's shiso.

1222
00:53:11,454 --> 00:53:13,623
-Shiso.
-Jong-won is using shiso.

1223
00:53:13,690 --> 00:53:14,991
He's using shiso.

1224
00:53:15,058 --> 00:53:16,760
It's different from perilla leaves.

1225
00:53:16,826 --> 00:53:18,361
THE EEL, THE BREAD

1226
00:53:18,428 --> 00:53:19,429
THE EEL

1227
00:53:19,496 --> 00:53:22,599
-Where did he get the eel from?
-It was in the oven.

1228
00:53:22,666 --> 00:53:25,202
JAPANESE-STYLE PICKLED CUCUMBERS

1229
00:53:25,835 --> 00:53:27,804
AVOCADO

1230
00:53:28,538 --> 00:53:29,839
HE CUTS IT IN HALF

1231
00:53:29,906 --> 00:53:31,675
AND CHOPS IT FINELY

1232
00:53:31,741 --> 00:53:33,476
He's using avocado.

1233
00:53:33,543 --> 00:53:34,611
And the eel.

1234
00:53:35,445 --> 00:53:36,446
He cuts it into three pieces.

1235
00:53:37,614 --> 00:53:38,848
EVENLY CUT

1236
00:53:38,915 --> 00:53:41,418
I think he's trying
to turn it into a roll.

1237
00:53:41,484 --> 00:53:44,354
Into the shiso leaves? I get it.

1238
00:53:44,421 --> 00:53:45,889
He added avocado inside too.

1239
00:53:45,956 --> 00:53:48,091
It's like a California roll.

1240
00:53:48,158 --> 00:53:49,626
If he wants to roll it up,

1241
00:53:49,693 --> 00:53:51,261
he'll have to use shiso leaves.

1242
00:53:51,328 --> 00:53:53,430
I see. And then what?

1243
00:53:53,496 --> 00:53:56,633
-He'll probably put it on the bread.
-After cutting it up?

1244
00:53:57,467 --> 00:53:59,836
He's making it completely circular.

1245
00:53:59,903 --> 00:54:01,905
THE SECOND TYPE OF PROTEIN,
EEL AND AVOCADO ROLLS

1246
00:54:03,073 --> 00:54:06,109
YUSUKE CHOOSES PERILLA LEAVES

1247
00:54:06,176 --> 00:54:09,279
He's a type who cooks very calmly,

1248
00:54:09,346 --> 00:54:13,250
but he has a determined way
of continuously moving forward.

1249
00:54:13,316 --> 00:54:15,051
-Like he's using magic to walk.
-Yes.

1250
00:54:15,118 --> 00:54:16,353
He continues to move forward.

1251
00:54:16,419 --> 00:54:17,954
You have just under nine minutes.

1252
00:54:19,456 --> 00:54:22,058
That's odd.
He mixed avocado and perilla leaves.

1253
00:54:22,125 --> 00:54:24,561
-And stir-fried kale!
-And kale.

1254
00:54:24,628 --> 00:54:26,229
It was cooked with meat and butter.

1255
00:54:26,296 --> 00:54:28,465
-What is that?
-He puts everything in.

1256
00:54:28,531 --> 00:54:32,168
-He put the meat in there.
-The bone broth.

1257
00:54:32,235 --> 00:54:34,271
He's making green purée.

1258
00:54:34,337 --> 00:54:36,940
It looks like Chef Yusuke will blend that.

1259
00:54:37,007 --> 00:54:39,242
-I wonder what it'll taste like.
-Kind of like pesto?

1260
00:54:39,309 --> 00:54:40,310
PUSHING

1261
00:54:40,377 --> 00:54:43,179
-I don't think it's working.
-Oh, no.

1262
00:54:43,246 --> 00:54:45,782
-It's not that button.
-Someone help him.

1263
00:54:45,849 --> 00:54:47,917
-He needs help.
-We need to help with that.

1264
00:54:47,984 --> 00:54:49,552
DON'T WORRY, MY FRIEND

1265
00:54:49,619 --> 00:54:51,321
Please give him a hand with the blender.

1266
00:54:52,222 --> 00:54:53,223
I think this is it.

1267
00:54:53,290 --> 00:54:55,492
-Like this.
-You have to push it in all the way.

1268
00:54:55,558 --> 00:54:57,594
This is bad. Did it work?

1269
00:54:57,661 --> 00:54:59,062
It's spinning around.

1270
00:54:59,129 --> 00:55:01,164
He lost about ten seconds here.

1271
00:55:01,231 --> 00:55:04,768
-It's not easy to work that thing.
-But Chef Yusuke isn't bothered.

1272
00:55:04,834 --> 00:55:07,470
This is a lot of fun to watch.

1273
00:55:07,537 --> 00:55:08,672
He doesn't have much time.

1274
00:55:08,738 --> 00:55:10,173
That broth must be important.

1275
00:55:10,874 --> 00:55:11,908
Gosh.

1276
00:55:11,975 --> 00:55:13,977
-He fishes out the meat.
-Gosh.

1277
00:55:14,044 --> 00:55:16,112
YUSUKE'S SECOND PROTEIN INGREDIENT

1278
00:55:16,179 --> 00:55:20,750
Chef Yusuke only seems to have
the main dishes ready.

1279
00:55:20,817 --> 00:55:22,819
I think the boiled meat is
probably for the noodles.

1280
00:55:22,886 --> 00:55:24,220
-I see.
-Right.

1281
00:55:24,287 --> 00:55:26,189
He'll serve the noodles
as the appetizer anyway.

1282
00:55:26,256 --> 00:55:27,457
THE NOODLES ARE DONE TOO

1283
00:55:27,524 --> 00:55:31,861
-How can he remain so composed?
-He's very calm.

1284
00:55:31,928 --> 00:55:33,129
He is.

1285
00:55:33,196 --> 00:55:34,964
He puts it under cold water.

1286
00:55:35,532 --> 00:55:37,000
JONG-WON HAD BEEN BOILING MILK TEA

1287
00:55:37,634 --> 00:55:39,235
ADDING HONEY

1288
00:55:40,203 --> 00:55:42,505
Gosh, it's so much fun to watch this.

1289
00:55:42,572 --> 00:55:44,574
7. ADD HONEY TO THE MILK TEA,
AND THEN COOL IN AN ICED BOWL

1290
00:55:46,343 --> 00:55:47,377
HE BEGINS TO MAKE
THE SIDE SAUCE FOR THE STEAK

1291
00:55:47,444 --> 00:55:49,045
-What's that sauce?
-What is that?

1292
00:55:49,112 --> 00:55:50,980
-Balsamic vinegar.
-Balsamic. That's Balsamic vinegar, bro.

1293
00:55:51,047 --> 00:55:53,149
-What's that?
-Balsamic vinegar.

1294
00:55:55,652 --> 00:55:56,720
WHAT'S NEXT?

1295
00:55:56,786 --> 00:55:58,421
-What are you doing, Jong-won?
-Cheese.

1296
00:55:58,488 --> 00:56:00,256
-He's making hash brown.
-Hash brown?

1297
00:56:00,323 --> 00:56:02,192
What? Hash brown? Right.

1298
00:56:02,258 --> 00:56:03,526
That's Sa-rang's stuff.

1299
00:56:03,593 --> 00:56:04,694
I'm not allowed to use that.

1300
00:56:04,761 --> 00:56:06,896
He wasn't allowed to use Sa-rang's stuff.

1301
00:56:06,963 --> 00:56:09,165
-You can't help it.
-I was joking.

1302
00:56:09,232 --> 00:56:11,668
WE THOUGHT YOU'D GET KICKED OUT

1303
00:56:11,735 --> 00:56:13,169
But it was Sa-rang's, anyway.

1304
00:56:13,870 --> 00:56:15,472
You should buy one for her.

1305
00:56:16,473 --> 00:56:18,575
He hasn't started the dessert yet.

1306
00:56:18,641 --> 00:56:19,843
Right?

1307
00:56:19,909 --> 00:56:21,378
Chef Yusuke uses Balsamic vinegar.

1308
00:56:21,444 --> 00:56:23,747
-They're using similar things.
-Yes.

1309
00:56:24,481 --> 00:56:26,583
BLACK PEPPER, OLIVE OIL

1310
00:56:26,649 --> 00:56:27,917
-Five minutes.
-Five minutes!

1311
00:56:27,984 --> 00:56:29,552
-Five minutes left.
-Okay.

1312
00:56:29,619 --> 00:56:31,521
-Hurry up.
-I feel stifled.

1313
00:56:31,588 --> 00:56:32,589
-Hurry.
-Please go out, Jung-hwan.

1314
00:56:32,655 --> 00:56:35,258
I've played in many Korea-Japan matches,

1315
00:56:35,325 --> 00:56:37,227
but it's my first time as a reporter.

1316
00:56:37,293 --> 00:56:39,462
The round is between Yusuke and Jong-won.

1317
00:56:39,529 --> 00:56:41,264
Chef Yusuke seems composed.

1318
00:56:41,331 --> 00:56:42,632
Why are they both so calm?

1319
00:56:42,699 --> 00:56:44,667
This must be the broth from the meat.
He continues to boil this.

1320
00:56:44,734 --> 00:56:45,835
Is this Balsamic vinegar?

1321
00:56:45,902 --> 00:56:47,070
JONG-WON IS DONE MAKING
THE BALSAMIC SAUCE FOR STEAK

1322
00:56:47,137 --> 00:56:49,172
The sauce. He's boiling the sauce down.

1323
00:56:49,239 --> 00:56:52,108
He must be using Balsamic vinegar
as his steak sauce.

1324
00:56:52,175 --> 00:56:54,210
I'm using both steak sauce
and Balsamic vinegar.

1325
00:56:54,277 --> 00:56:56,079
I see. You're using both.

1326
00:56:56,146 --> 00:56:58,081
-The heat is off. Is the steak done?
-It is.

1327
00:56:58,148 --> 00:57:00,450
The steak is done.
The heat is already off.

1328
00:57:01,518 --> 00:57:04,687
Silken tofu.

1329
00:57:04,754 --> 00:57:06,723
CUTTING SIDEWAYS!

1330
00:57:07,290 --> 00:57:08,324
The dessert.

1331
00:57:08,391 --> 00:57:10,493
You have to start the dessert ready.

1332
00:57:10,560 --> 00:57:11,995
He's using red bean paste too.

1333
00:57:12,061 --> 00:57:14,631
The dessert. That must be the dessert.

1334
00:57:15,198 --> 00:57:20,270
10. SERVE IN THE ORDER OF RED BEAN PASTE,
SILKEN TOFU, AND MILK TEA TO MAKE DESSERT

1335
00:57:20,770 --> 00:57:22,472
JONG-WON IS DONE WITH HIS DESSERT

1336
00:57:22,539 --> 00:57:24,040
BUTTER

1337
00:57:24,607 --> 00:57:26,309
Why is the pan so hot?

1338
00:57:26,376 --> 00:57:29,078
I think he'll pull out the meat
from the aluminum foil.

1339
00:57:29,145 --> 00:57:32,081
-And he cooks the meat once again!
-That's it!

1340
00:57:32,148 --> 00:57:34,250
He's doing that at four minutes.

1341
00:57:34,317 --> 00:57:36,319
That's extremely high heat.

1342
00:57:36,386 --> 00:57:38,555
Many people cook steak like that in Japan.

1343
00:57:38,621 --> 00:57:40,757
They sear the outside toward the end.

1344
00:57:40,824 --> 00:57:41,991
It's reversed searing.

1345
00:57:42,058 --> 00:57:45,028
I see. Is this reversed searing?

1346
00:57:45,094 --> 00:57:47,964
That's a modern way,
the most recent way of cooking steak.

1347
00:57:48,031 --> 00:57:50,300
Yes, that's the fad these days.

1348
00:57:50,366 --> 00:57:53,903
-He's working hard on the steak.
-He is.

1349
00:57:53,970 --> 00:57:54,971
Chef Yusuke.

1350
00:57:55,038 --> 00:57:57,440
-He's focused on the meat.
-Yes.

1351
00:57:58,107 --> 00:57:59,509
EMBARRASSED

1352
00:57:59,576 --> 00:58:01,277
It smells wonderful.

1353
00:58:01,344 --> 00:58:04,280
THE STEAK IS READY

1354
00:58:04,814 --> 00:58:07,317
This is a fight
between Yusuke and Jong-won.

1355
00:58:07,383 --> 00:58:09,686
Will they have enough time?

1356
00:58:09,752 --> 00:58:12,555
He just cut this.

1357
00:58:12,622 --> 00:58:14,991
I hope it doesn't fall apart.

1358
00:58:15,058 --> 00:58:16,292
It won't get cut so easily.

1359
00:58:17,060 --> 00:58:19,295
He's very detailed.

1360
00:58:20,029 --> 00:58:21,865
I hope it doesn't fall through.

1361
00:58:23,399 --> 00:58:24,400
That shape…

1362
00:58:24,467 --> 00:58:25,702
HE SWITCHES THE KNIFE AGAIN

1363
00:58:26,836 --> 00:58:28,338
HE FINISHES CUTTING

1364
00:58:29,138 --> 00:58:31,441
ALL HE HAS TO DO NOW IS
UNRAVEL THE PLASTIC WRAP

1365
00:58:31,508 --> 00:58:33,743
Jong-won's hands are trembling.

1366
00:58:33,810 --> 00:58:35,478
TREMBLING

1367
00:58:35,545 --> 00:58:37,313
DID HE SUCCEED?

1368
00:58:37,380 --> 00:58:38,715
One of the pieces fell apart!

1369
00:58:38,781 --> 00:58:39,883
HOW DREADFUL
HE MUST THROW IT OUT!

1370
00:58:41,317 --> 00:58:43,720
-One piece of eel is gone.
-One piece of eel is unsalvageable.

1371
00:58:43,786 --> 00:58:46,122
-One piece of eel is gone.
-One piece of eel is unsalvageable.

1372
00:58:46,923 --> 00:58:48,658
-He saved one.
-He did?

1373
00:58:48,725 --> 00:58:51,361
-He saved one eel piece.
-I see.

1374
00:58:51,427 --> 00:58:54,063
Isn't this hash brown getting burnt?

1375
00:58:54,130 --> 00:58:56,666
One second.

1376
00:59:00,236 --> 00:59:01,437
I was just letting you know.

1377
00:59:01,504 --> 00:59:03,940
-Thanks a lot.
-I was just letting you know.

1378
00:59:04,774 --> 00:59:08,077
-You have about three minutes left.
-Three minutes.

1379
00:59:08,144 --> 00:59:09,312
Chef Yusuke.

1380
00:59:10,246 --> 00:59:12,515
You're running out of time.
What about your dessert?

1381
00:59:13,082 --> 00:59:14,484
BLACK SESAME POWDER

1382
00:59:14,551 --> 00:59:17,153
He's mixing it with black sesame powder.

1383
00:59:17,220 --> 00:59:19,923
-He's using black sesame.
-Black sesame?

1384
00:59:19,989 --> 00:59:21,624
Gosh, that's amazing.

1385
00:59:22,525 --> 00:59:24,994
-The noodles are done.
-He cooled the noodles.

1386
00:59:25,061 --> 00:59:28,197
-The noodles, the broth, and…
-The broth, and the meat.

1387
00:59:28,264 --> 00:59:30,867
THE NOODLES ARE THE APPETIZER

1388
00:59:31,668 --> 00:59:33,303
THE BONE BROTH THAT COOKED THE MEAT

1389
00:59:33,369 --> 00:59:35,638
He's pouring the broth
that cooked the meat over the noodles.

1390
00:59:35,705 --> 00:59:37,874
-It's like Vietnamese noodles.
-He's using that soup.

1391
00:59:37,941 --> 00:59:40,977
-That looks so good.
-Man!

1392
00:59:41,044 --> 00:59:42,812
IT'S HIS KIND OF DISH

1393
00:59:44,147 --> 00:59:46,015
Look at the meat.

1394
00:59:46,082 --> 00:59:48,518
Gosh, I'm in trouble.

1395
00:59:49,419 --> 00:59:52,488
-And cilantro?
-Man, cilantro!

1396
00:59:52,555 --> 00:59:56,125
-He topped the noodles with cilantro.
-That looks so good.

1397
00:59:56,192 --> 00:59:59,796
-It's for his hangover, right?
-It's like Japanese cuisine.

1398
00:59:59,862 --> 01:00:01,264
The noodles are done.

1399
01:00:01,331 --> 01:00:03,700
The appetizer is done.

1400
01:00:03,766 --> 01:00:05,969
-And a piece of lemon.
-He got the noodles ready.

1401
01:00:06,035 --> 01:00:07,537
JONG-WON IS GETTING BUSIER

1402
01:00:08,237 --> 01:00:10,239
THE BREAD GOT TOASTED UNTIL GOLDEN BROWN

1403
01:00:10,306 --> 01:00:12,809
-A minute and 40 seconds.
-A minute and 40 seconds. Mind the time.

1404
01:00:13,509 --> 01:00:16,713
11. TOP TOASTED BREAD
WITH THE EEL AND AVOCADO ROLL

1405
01:00:17,347 --> 01:00:18,848
Jong-won begins to serve his food.

1406
01:00:18,915 --> 01:00:21,884
-You don't have much time.
-A minute and 30 seconds.

1407
01:00:21,951 --> 01:00:24,887
-A minute and 30 seconds.
-Your dessert.

1408
01:00:24,954 --> 01:00:29,025
You have to cut off the thread.
Gosh, isn't it hot?

1409
01:00:29,092 --> 01:00:30,927
He can't cut off the string!

1410
01:00:30,994 --> 01:00:33,396
He can't cut off the string!

1411
01:00:35,131 --> 01:00:37,200
HE GOT IT UNDONE!

1412
01:00:37,700 --> 01:00:41,037
-It came undone.
-Man, I couldn't breathe.

1413
01:00:41,104 --> 01:00:43,172
Jong-won's meat is ready.

1414
01:00:43,239 --> 01:00:45,708
-One minute.
-You don't have much time.

1415
01:00:45,775 --> 01:00:47,610
Hurry up.

1416
01:00:47,677 --> 01:00:48,811
That thing.

1417
01:00:49,879 --> 01:00:51,381
HE'S DOING HIS BEST

1418
01:00:52,548 --> 01:00:53,549
HE GRABS A TOWEL

1419
01:00:54,617 --> 01:00:56,953
-Fabri, help him out.
-Me?

1420
01:00:57,020 --> 01:00:59,255
That thing… Never mind, he got it.
He opened it.

1421
01:01:00,289 --> 01:01:01,391
HE'S PUTTING IT DOWN,
SCOOPING, AND SERVING

1422
01:01:01,457 --> 01:01:04,427
Chef Yusuke is finally moving quickly.

1423
01:01:04,494 --> 01:01:05,928
He's a bit faster now.

1424
01:01:06,896 --> 01:01:09,465
-He's finally moving.
-Chef Yusuke is finally moving quickly.

1425
01:01:09,532 --> 01:01:11,734
He could move quickly.

1426
01:01:11,801 --> 01:01:13,169
Whipped cream and what?

1427
01:01:13,236 --> 01:01:16,205
You have a minute left.

1428
01:01:18,341 --> 01:01:19,542
JONG-WON STILL HAS A LONG WAY TO GO

1429
01:01:20,276 --> 01:01:22,345
WHAT'S HE SLICING AS THINLY AS PAPER?

1430
01:01:22,412 --> 01:01:23,746
What are those? mushrooms?

1431
01:01:23,813 --> 01:01:26,683
-Button mushrooms.
-He's slicing button mushrooms.

1432
01:01:26,749 --> 01:01:28,885
-Come on! Fifty seconds!
-Fifty seconds.

1433
01:01:29,485 --> 01:01:31,621
Hey, what is this?

1434
01:01:32,121 --> 01:01:33,256
FEELING ANXIOUS

1435
01:01:33,322 --> 01:01:35,625
HE HAS NO TIME!

1436
01:01:35,692 --> 01:01:38,594
JONG-WON JUST HAS TO SERVE HIS MAIN DISH

1437
01:01:39,295 --> 01:01:43,533
12. MAKE DRESSING BY MIXING PLAIN YOGURT,
CRUSHED GARLIC, AND LEMON JUICE

1438
01:01:44,200 --> 01:01:45,968
Jong-won is looking busy too.

1439
01:01:46,035 --> 01:01:47,470
You have 40 seconds left!

1440
01:01:47,537 --> 01:01:50,273
-You have 40 seconds left!
-You have to move faster!

1441
01:01:50,339 --> 01:01:52,408
Chef Yusuke looks busy.

1442
01:01:53,142 --> 01:01:54,977
REMAINING CALM

1443
01:01:55,044 --> 01:01:57,613
Chef Yusuke's hands are trembling!

1444
01:01:57,680 --> 01:01:59,582
12. TOP RED BEAN PASTE WITH YOGURT CREAM

1445
01:01:59,649 --> 01:02:01,984
Come on! Thirty seconds!

1446
01:02:02,719 --> 01:02:03,786
You have to stop!

1447
01:02:04,353 --> 01:02:07,323
YUSUKE FINISHES THE DESSERT

1448
01:02:07,390 --> 01:02:09,459
The meat.

1449
01:02:09,525 --> 01:02:10,626
The main dish.

1450
01:02:10,693 --> 01:02:12,095
The main isn't there.

1451
01:02:12,662 --> 01:02:15,198
BOTH CHEFS AREN'T DONE WITH THE MAIN DISH!

1452
01:02:16,332 --> 01:02:17,934
ROASTED HASH BROWN

1453
01:02:18,901 --> 01:02:21,637
HE BEGINS TO SERVE THE MAIN DISH!

1454
01:02:21,704 --> 01:02:24,040
CHEF YUSUKE GETS STARTED
ON THE MAIN DISH TOO

1455
01:02:24,107 --> 01:02:26,275
The main dish, the steak.

1456
01:02:26,342 --> 01:02:28,511
-The steak!
-Twenty seconds.

1457
01:02:28,578 --> 01:02:30,713
-Twenty seconds.
-You can do this.

1458
01:02:31,280 --> 01:02:33,449
MIXING BUTTON MUSHROOMS WITH SALAD

1459
01:02:33,516 --> 01:02:35,284
AND TOPPING IT ON THE STEAK

1460
01:02:35,351 --> 01:02:37,386
IT GOES ON TOP OF THE HASH BROWN

1461
01:02:37,453 --> 01:02:38,621
Ten seconds.

1462
01:02:38,688 --> 01:02:40,623
You don't have much time left.

1463
01:02:44,093 --> 01:02:45,428
-Eight. Seven.
-Eight. Seven.

1464
01:02:45,495 --> 01:02:47,497
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

1465
01:02:47,563 --> 01:02:49,832
-Ten seconds. Eight. Seven.
-Eight. Seven.

1466
01:02:49,899 --> 01:02:52,135
-Six. Five.
-Six. Five.

1467
01:02:52,201 --> 01:02:54,237
-Four. Three.
-Four. Three.

1468
01:02:54,303 --> 01:02:56,339
-Two. One.
-Chef Jong-won ends first.

1469
01:02:56,405 --> 01:02:57,607
Last touch, Chef Yusuke.

1470
01:03:00,042 --> 01:03:02,879
CHEF YUSUKE FINISHES TAKADA-LICIOUS

1471
01:03:02,945 --> 01:03:05,281
THAT WAS A HISTORIC MATCH!

1472
01:03:05,782 --> 01:03:08,117
-That was amazing.
-My gosh.

1473
01:03:09,352 --> 01:03:10,386
That was crazy.

1474
01:03:10,953 --> 01:03:13,823
ASIA'S 50 BEST RESTAURANTS SPECIAL,
THE KOREA-JAPAN MATCH IS OVER

1475
01:03:13,890 --> 01:03:15,191
Everything is out.

1476
01:03:15,258 --> 01:03:16,392
How could this happen?

1477
01:03:16,459 --> 01:03:18,060
My gosh. Whoa.

1478
01:03:18,127 --> 01:03:20,596
EVERYONE STANDS UP

1479
01:03:20,663 --> 01:03:22,331
These were all done in 15 minutes.

1480
01:03:22,398 --> 01:03:26,702
And now, these protein-rich dishes were
prepared just for you, Sung-hoon.

1481
01:03:26,769 --> 01:03:28,604
-Thank you.
-Sure.

1482
01:03:28,671 --> 01:03:32,175
First of all,
Sung-hoon seems quite pleased.

1483
01:03:32,241 --> 01:03:35,011
I know it's not easy to make three dishes

1484
01:03:35,077 --> 01:03:36,612
in just 15 minutes.

1485
01:03:36,679 --> 01:03:39,749
I could see
the power of these professional chefs.

1486
01:03:39,816 --> 01:03:42,752
Chef Yusuke, did everything go
just as you planned?

1487
01:03:42,819 --> 01:03:45,721
It was nothing like it.

1488
01:03:45,788 --> 01:03:48,324
-It looks great.
-It looks perfect to us.

1489
01:03:48,391 --> 01:03:50,026
I needed just another minute.

1490
01:03:51,427 --> 01:03:53,296
-The perk.
-You should've used the perk.

1491
01:03:53,362 --> 01:03:55,898
-See? You could've used it.
-Right?

1492
01:03:55,965 --> 01:03:57,133
You could've started a minute earlier.

1493
01:03:57,200 --> 01:03:59,569
-Now you're saying that?
-It's because of the Osaka style.

1494
01:03:59,635 --> 01:04:01,571
-You said people from Osaka wouldn't.
-We won't.

1495
01:04:01,637 --> 01:04:03,773
I'm just sharing what I felt in my heart.

1496
01:04:03,840 --> 01:04:07,109
HE ALMOST COULDN'T FINISH,
TRYING TO KEEP HIS OSAKA PERSONALITY

1497
01:04:07,610 --> 01:04:09,378
Jong-won, did it go as planned?

1498
01:04:09,445 --> 01:04:10,713
I'm not so sure.

1499
01:04:10,780 --> 01:04:12,648
THE EEL AND AVOCADO TOAST
HAD FALLEN APART IN THE PROCESS

1500
01:04:12,715 --> 01:04:14,417
I should've served two pieces.

1501
01:04:14,483 --> 01:04:15,818
-Two pieces?
-I see.

1502
01:04:15,885 --> 01:04:18,387
-One of them came undone, and that was it.
-What a shame.

1503
01:04:18,454 --> 01:04:20,423
-All right.
-It probably isn't easy.

1504
01:04:20,990 --> 01:04:24,126
THE BEST WAY TO RECHARGE,
EEL AND AVOCADO TOAST

1505
01:04:24,627 --> 01:04:28,598
AND TENDERLOIN STEAK WILL
MAKE UP FOR YOUR MUSCLE LOSS

1506
01:04:29,899 --> 01:04:32,301
SERVED WITH SWEET SILKEN TOFU DESSERT

1507
01:04:32,835 --> 01:04:36,005
CHEF SON JONG-WON'S CHOO-ROTEIN SWEEP

1508
01:04:36,072 --> 01:04:37,139
SNIFF

1509
01:04:37,206 --> 01:04:39,275
-It smells like eels.
-Yes.

1510
01:04:39,342 --> 01:04:43,946
He cooked a three-course meal
with protein from your fridge.

1511
01:04:44,013 --> 01:04:47,016
First, the eel and avocado toast.

1512
01:04:47,083 --> 01:04:49,685
Please try that all at once.
Make it look cool.

1513
01:04:49,752 --> 01:04:50,920
Okay. I understand.

1514
01:04:50,987 --> 01:04:53,189
-Now, the protein round.
-Wait.

1515
01:04:53,256 --> 01:04:55,925
-I need rice wine to eat eels.
-Again?

1516
01:04:55,992 --> 01:04:57,226
That again?

1517
01:04:57,293 --> 01:04:59,595
Come on. Stop it with the rice wine.

1518
01:04:59,662 --> 01:05:01,364
-He had to get it.
-Wait.

1519
01:05:01,430 --> 01:05:03,799
-I kept it in the freezer.
-He put it in there.

1520
01:05:03,866 --> 01:05:05,635
Are you looking for another glass?

1521
01:05:05,701 --> 01:05:09,472
Those are all just decorations.

1522
01:05:10,640 --> 01:05:12,375
THOSE ARE JUST DECORATIONS, SIR…

1523
01:05:12,441 --> 01:05:14,043
-Mister.
-Mister.

1524
01:05:14,110 --> 01:05:15,278
Come on, Mister.

1525
01:05:15,344 --> 01:05:18,147
-He pours that rice wine.
-I love his character.

1526
01:05:18,214 --> 01:05:19,982
That's the Osaka style.

1527
01:05:20,049 --> 01:05:21,817
-Gosh.
-It's like watching a drama.

1528
01:05:21,884 --> 01:05:23,252
-Thank you for the food.
-Yes.

1529
01:05:23,319 --> 01:05:24,587
Chef Jong-won's dishes.

1530
01:05:24,654 --> 01:05:27,323
First, he tries the appetizer
in a single bite.

1531
01:05:28,491 --> 01:05:29,892
He put eels in there.

1532
01:05:29,959 --> 01:05:31,661
-Eels and what else?
-Avocado.

1533
01:05:31,727 --> 01:05:36,098
I mixed eels, avocado,
and pickled veggies in the fridge,

1534
01:05:36,165 --> 01:05:37,233
cucumbers and plums.

1535
01:05:37,300 --> 01:05:39,568
-He mixed all the good stuff.
-And shiso.

1536
01:05:39,635 --> 01:05:41,570
There are lots of flavors.

1537
01:05:41,637 --> 01:05:43,005
I've never had anything like this before.

1538
01:05:44,206 --> 01:05:48,577
I can taste both eel and avocado,

1539
01:05:48,644 --> 01:05:51,113
and the bread kicks in at the end.

1540
01:05:51,180 --> 01:05:53,349
I loved the texture.

1541
01:05:53,416 --> 01:05:54,984
-The bread?
-Yes, there was the bread.

1542
01:05:55,051 --> 01:05:57,753
-It's the bread.
-He toasted it in the oven.

1543
01:05:57,820 --> 01:05:59,922
-It's good.
-The smell of the eel… Is it?

1544
01:06:00,589 --> 01:06:03,392
-But come on, it's time for meat.
-Time for meat.

1545
01:06:03,459 --> 01:06:05,227
He's about to devour the meat.

1546
01:06:05,294 --> 01:06:07,797
I have to watch him eat this.

1547
01:06:07,863 --> 01:06:09,432
SWITCHING SEATS

1548
01:06:09,498 --> 01:06:12,468
He's going to start eating the steak.

1549
01:06:12,535 --> 01:06:14,537
-The lion.
-This is the main dish.

1550
01:06:14,603 --> 01:06:17,006
It's the main dish.

1551
01:06:17,073 --> 01:06:19,842
-Try it with the veggies.
-Wait!

1552
01:06:19,909 --> 01:06:21,243
He destroyed it!

1553
01:06:21,310 --> 01:06:24,513
Jong-won did his best
to make it look so pretty!

1554
01:06:25,081 --> 01:06:26,949
BYE, VEGGIES

1555
01:06:27,016 --> 01:06:28,551
He destroyed it!

1556
01:06:28,617 --> 01:06:31,554
Jong-won did his best
to make it look so pretty!

1557
01:06:31,620 --> 01:06:33,289
HE JUST CUTS THE STEAK IN HALF

1558
01:06:33,990 --> 01:06:35,358
IT GOES STRAIGHT INTO HIS MOUTH

1559
01:06:35,424 --> 01:06:37,293
-It has to be good.
-He cuts it in half.

1560
01:06:37,360 --> 01:06:39,862
-He had half a steak in one bite.
-Yes.

1561
01:06:39,929 --> 01:06:43,733
-He doesn't care for veggies right now.
-All he wants is meat.

1562
01:06:43,799 --> 01:06:45,434
HE'S SUCH A WONDER

1563
01:06:45,501 --> 01:06:47,970
THE LION IS PLEASED

1564
01:06:48,037 --> 01:06:51,173
-The sauce is excellent.
-The sauce is good.

1565
01:06:51,240 --> 01:06:55,845
And the temperature seems to be perfect,
around 65 degrees Celsius.

1566
01:06:55,911 --> 01:06:58,014
You can tell those things with your mouth?

1567
01:06:58,080 --> 01:06:59,548
A THUMBS-UP WITH A KNIFE IN HIS HAND

1568
01:07:00,416 --> 01:07:01,984
He even checked the temperature.

1569
01:07:02,051 --> 01:07:03,586
A BIG BITE

1570
01:07:03,652 --> 01:07:05,154
He even checked the temperature.

1571
01:07:05,221 --> 01:07:09,325
HE FINISHES IT IN TWO BITES

1572
01:07:09,392 --> 01:07:11,460
He cut it in half,
and had half a steak with each bite.

1573
01:07:12,294 --> 01:07:14,997
Gosh, Sung-hoon.

1574
01:07:15,064 --> 01:07:17,366
-Goodbye, veggies.
-He has some veggies left.

1575
01:07:17,933 --> 01:07:19,201
NOPE

1576
01:07:19,969 --> 01:07:21,370
THANKS FOR THE FOOD

1577
01:07:22,405 --> 01:07:24,974
He spent such a long time
trying to put those together!

1578
01:07:25,041 --> 01:07:26,475
He spent some time on that.

1579
01:07:26,542 --> 01:07:29,211
What's more important is protein.

1580
01:07:30,346 --> 01:07:32,481
-But try some for his sake.
-He's picking on the salad.

1581
01:07:32,982 --> 01:07:35,151
-He's looking for missing meat.
-"What's here?"

1582
01:07:35,217 --> 01:07:37,553
There was no meat!

1583
01:07:37,620 --> 01:07:39,755
HE CONFIRMED THE FACT

1584
01:07:39,822 --> 01:07:42,058
-He just checked for leftover meat.
-Just checking.

1585
01:07:42,124 --> 01:07:44,860
He checked to see
if he missed any pieces of meat.

1586
01:07:44,927 --> 01:07:47,563
But still, the meat was really good.

1587
01:07:47,630 --> 01:07:48,964
Thank you.

1588
01:07:49,031 --> 01:07:50,833
-Was the meat good?
-That string around the meat

1589
01:07:50,900 --> 01:07:53,235
must've played a part.

1590
01:07:53,936 --> 01:07:55,538
Was this Balsamic sauce?

1591
01:07:55,604 --> 01:07:57,973
-I mixed Balsamic and your steak sauce.
-Right?

1592
01:07:58,040 --> 01:07:59,642
I could totally taste that.

1593
01:07:59,708 --> 01:08:02,478
It was a type of sauce
I usually like to eat.

1594
01:08:03,112 --> 01:08:04,413
And now, the dessert.

1595
01:08:05,448 --> 01:08:07,216
-This was made with protein too.
-Yes.

1596
01:08:08,451 --> 01:08:10,152
Was it yuja?

1597
01:08:10,219 --> 01:08:12,254
-I put in some black tea.
-Black tea?

1598
01:08:12,321 --> 01:08:14,056
HE INFUSED BLACK TEA IN BOILING MILK

1599
01:08:14,123 --> 01:08:17,193
-It was black tea?
-I get it.

1600
01:08:17,259 --> 01:08:19,528
-And red bean paste too.
-Yes, it's at the bottom.

1601
01:08:19,595 --> 01:08:21,330
Which style of cuisine is this…

1602
01:08:21,397 --> 01:08:22,865
RED BEAN PASTE SHOWS UP

1603
01:08:22,932 --> 01:08:24,366
My gosh.

1604
01:08:24,934 --> 01:08:25,935
What's he doing?

1605
01:08:26,001 --> 01:08:27,703
-It's like panna cotta.
-Yes.

1606
01:08:28,737 --> 01:08:30,973
-What's it like?
-I wonder what it's like.

1607
01:08:31,040 --> 01:08:32,708
-And…
-Silken tofu and red bean paste.

1608
01:08:34,076 --> 01:08:36,912
ENJOYING

1609
01:08:36,979 --> 01:08:38,380
That was so close.

1610
01:08:38,447 --> 01:08:40,649
-What was close?
-How was it close?

1611
01:08:40,716 --> 01:08:43,118
I loved the idea,

1612
01:08:43,185 --> 01:08:45,788
but it's not as sweet as I like it to be.

1613
01:08:45,855 --> 01:08:49,625
-If I were him, I'd make it sweeter.
-Yes, after all, it's dessert.

1614
01:08:49,692 --> 01:08:52,995
-He eats chocolate in piles and stacks.
-Yes.

1615
01:08:53,062 --> 01:08:54,396
But it was a great idea.

1616
01:08:54,463 --> 01:08:56,065
BUT HE STILL POPS IT IN AT ONCE

1617
01:08:56,132 --> 01:08:57,366
FULLY CHARGED WITH PROTEIN

1618
01:08:58,033 --> 01:09:00,169
HE EATS EVERYTHING IN ONE BITE

1619
01:09:00,236 --> 01:09:02,104
That was delicious.

1620
01:09:03,205 --> 01:09:04,640
Have a sip of rice wine.

1621
01:09:06,041 --> 01:09:07,743
-This wine is delicious.
-I see.

1622
01:09:08,644 --> 01:09:11,213
Next, Chef Yusuke's dishes.

1623
01:09:11,280 --> 01:09:14,884
TWO LUMPS OF TENDERLOIN STEAK
MADE JUST FOR THE MACHO MAN

1624
01:09:15,384 --> 01:09:17,820
NOODLES WITH LOTS OF MEAT

1625
01:09:17,887 --> 01:09:20,289
AND REFRESHING DESSERT

1626
01:09:20,789 --> 01:09:25,461
CHEF YUSUKE'S TAKADA-LICIOUS

1627
01:09:25,528 --> 01:09:27,530
-First, the noodles.
-Should I start with the noodles?

1628
01:09:27,596 --> 01:09:29,598
-Start with the noodles.
-Okay.

1629
01:09:30,699 --> 01:09:32,601
Should I squeeze out the lemon juice?

1630
01:09:32,668 --> 01:09:33,969
-As you like it.
-Okay.

1631
01:09:34,036 --> 01:09:36,071
-The lemon.
-He's picking it up.

1632
01:09:38,674 --> 01:09:40,743
SQUEEZE

1633
01:09:41,577 --> 01:09:43,913
The lemon is in so much pain.

1634
01:09:43,979 --> 01:09:46,582
-He's the human juicer.
-Yes, the lemon is in pain.

1635
01:09:46,649 --> 01:09:47,983
Thank you for the food.

1636
01:09:48,951 --> 01:09:50,486
SLURPING ON THE SOUP FIRST

1637
01:09:50,553 --> 01:09:53,289
-He made the soup with bone broth.
-He did.

1638
01:09:53,355 --> 01:09:55,457
THE SOUP IS A PASS

1639
01:09:56,025 --> 01:09:57,026
BOWING

1640
01:09:57,760 --> 01:09:59,228
THIS TIME, THE NOODLES

1641
01:09:59,862 --> 01:10:02,464
A LOAD OF MEAT

1642
01:10:02,531 --> 01:10:05,868
-Yes, there was meat inside.
-Yes, the meat.

1643
01:10:06,435 --> 01:10:08,204
PLEASED

1644
01:10:08,771 --> 01:10:11,640
THIS IS THE GENEROSITY
OF AN OSAKA MAN FOR MEAT

1645
01:10:11,707 --> 01:10:12,875
Do that again.

1646
01:10:14,009 --> 01:10:15,277
That really suits Sung-hoon.

1647
01:10:15,344 --> 01:10:18,380
-That was awesome.
-That was almost violent.

1648
01:10:18,447 --> 01:10:20,649
-The noodles go well with him.
-He tries a bite.

1649
01:10:20,716 --> 01:10:22,184
The noodles and the meat.

1650
01:10:22,251 --> 01:10:24,753
-Did it turn out well?
-It looked good.

1651
01:10:24,820 --> 01:10:26,622
MY MOUTH IS WATERING…

1652
01:10:26,689 --> 01:10:29,291
-That's what we call noodles with meat.
-Yes.

1653
01:10:30,192 --> 01:10:33,062
He has such a manly way of eating.

1654
01:10:33,128 --> 01:10:36,498
-My mouth is watering.
-Yes, mine too.

1655
01:10:37,066 --> 01:10:38,200
A GENEROUS AMOUNT OF NOODLES

1656
01:10:38,267 --> 01:10:40,502
SLURP

1657
01:10:41,403 --> 01:10:43,038
My mouth waters just by watching him.

1658
01:10:43,639 --> 01:10:45,441
I HAVE TO GET THIS ON CAMERA

1659
01:10:46,008 --> 01:10:47,977
EVERYONE TAKES THEIR OWN VIDEO

1660
01:10:48,043 --> 01:10:49,645
I shouldn't drool over his food.

1661
01:10:49,712 --> 01:10:52,147
This is what I call a mukbang.

1662
01:10:52,214 --> 01:10:54,016
YOON NAM-NO'S CAM

1663
01:10:54,083 --> 01:10:55,851
Gosh, this is just…

1664
01:10:55,918 --> 01:10:57,286
Hey, stop filming me.

1665
01:10:59,154 --> 01:11:02,324
This is still the appetizer.

1666
01:11:02,391 --> 01:11:04,126
He eats so deliciously.

1667
01:11:04,193 --> 01:11:05,594
HAPPY

1668
01:11:05,661 --> 01:11:08,530
I thought he had topped
too much cilantro on top,

1669
01:11:08,597 --> 01:11:09,598
but that wasn't the case.

1670
01:11:09,665 --> 01:11:12,134
I realized it was perfect after I had it.

1671
01:11:12,201 --> 01:11:14,570
-Cilantro.
-It works well with the greasy taste.

1672
01:11:15,604 --> 01:11:17,306
It must keep the dish
from tasting too greasy.

1673
01:11:17,873 --> 01:11:21,277
-I'm getting full from just watching.
-Right?

1674
01:11:21,343 --> 01:11:23,746
-Gosh.
-Hey, will you start chewing?

1675
01:11:23,812 --> 01:11:24,913
Did you even chew?

1676
01:11:24,980 --> 01:11:28,217
-He hasn't even had the steak.
-You're right.

1677
01:11:28,284 --> 01:11:29,351
That's a huge portion.

1678
01:11:29,418 --> 01:11:31,553
-It's like YouTube on my phone.
-Right?

1679
01:11:31,620 --> 01:11:33,856
Everything had been calculated.

1680
01:11:34,957 --> 01:11:37,426
It's been a while,
but the noodles didn't get too soggy.

1681
01:11:37,493 --> 01:11:38,727
-They didn't?
-No.

1682
01:11:38,794 --> 01:11:40,129
It's because he washed them in cold water.

1683
01:11:40,195 --> 01:11:41,997
-Onto the main dish.
-The main dish.

1684
01:11:42,064 --> 01:11:44,133
This is good.

1685
01:11:44,199 --> 01:11:47,369
-"This is good."
-"This is good."

1686
01:11:47,436 --> 01:11:49,805
-This is amazing.
-Was that his Osaka dialect?

1687
01:11:50,906 --> 01:11:54,276
-Now, onto the main dish.
-The main dish. He worked hard on it.

1688
01:11:54,343 --> 01:11:58,047
I'll try just the meat without the sauce.

1689
01:11:58,113 --> 01:12:00,316
CHOMPING

1690
01:12:00,382 --> 01:12:01,216
SAVORING

1691
01:12:01,283 --> 01:12:03,085
Is it Takada-licious?

1692
01:12:03,152 --> 01:12:05,287
-Takada-licious.
-Is it Takada-licious?

1693
01:12:05,354 --> 01:12:08,190
IS IT?

1694
01:12:08,257 --> 01:12:10,959
-It goes well together.
-It goes well?

1695
01:12:11,026 --> 01:12:12,227
RELIEVED

1696
01:12:12,294 --> 01:12:16,899
It's been salted nicely,
so the meat itself is already good.

1697
01:12:17,833 --> 01:12:21,370
-He topped it with something.
-I have to try it with the sauce.

1698
01:12:21,437 --> 01:12:24,139
He cooked just the way I like it.

1699
01:12:24,206 --> 01:12:26,475
Completely rare.

1700
01:12:26,542 --> 01:12:28,177
-He knew what you liked.
-The bloody meat.

1701
01:12:30,979 --> 01:12:33,082
ENJOYING!

1702
01:12:33,649 --> 01:12:35,551
What's this sauce?

1703
01:12:35,617 --> 01:12:36,785
It was kale.

1704
01:12:36,852 --> 01:12:39,221
A mix of kale and perilla leaf.

1705
01:12:40,189 --> 01:12:42,925
It must've been good
even though it was made with veggies.

1706
01:12:42,991 --> 01:12:47,463
That's how mothers cook veggies
for their children who hate them.

1707
01:12:48,230 --> 01:12:49,965
Our baby Sung-hoon has changed.

1708
01:12:51,467 --> 01:12:53,001
Nobody would resist these veggies.

1709
01:12:53,068 --> 01:12:54,636
-He can eat it like that.
-Of course.

1710
01:12:55,204 --> 01:12:57,606
-He made dessert too.
-Yes, he did.

1711
01:12:57,673 --> 01:12:59,675
-The knife…
-The knife…

1712
01:12:59,742 --> 01:13:03,212
He just put the knife in his mouth
like this was a magic show or something.

1713
01:13:03,278 --> 01:13:05,814
I thought you were doing a magic show.

1714
01:13:05,881 --> 01:13:07,850
THE MIDDLE-AGED MAN'S MUKBANG IS
FULL OF SPECTACLES

1715
01:13:07,916 --> 01:13:10,819
-He didn't even eat the tomatoes.
-The tomatoes.

1716
01:13:10,886 --> 01:13:13,021
He worked hard on those!

1717
01:13:13,088 --> 01:13:14,423
Please try just one.

1718
01:13:15,190 --> 01:13:17,559
-He can eat it, though.
-He tries a piece of tomato.

1719
01:13:17,626 --> 01:13:21,063
WILL IT PASS?

1720
01:13:21,130 --> 01:13:22,197
It's so-so.

1721
01:13:23,866 --> 01:13:25,934
THE TOMATO DIDN'T COME WITH A TWIST

1722
01:13:26,001 --> 01:13:28,871
-A tomato is a tomato.
-It's still a tomato.

1723
01:13:28,937 --> 01:13:31,607
The tomato tasted like tomato.

1724
01:13:32,307 --> 01:13:34,977
It doesn't matter what you do.
I can't enjoy it.

1725
01:13:35,911 --> 01:13:38,280
-He should eat the meat.
-Yes, it's the meat.

1726
01:13:38,847 --> 01:13:41,350
Most guests share their dish with others.

1727
01:13:41,417 --> 01:13:42,451
Gosh, that old man.

1728
01:13:42,518 --> 01:13:44,086
2 BITES

1729
01:13:44,887 --> 01:13:46,789
He won't touch the veggies.

1730
01:13:46,855 --> 01:13:49,057
Sung-hoon doesn't tell a lie.

1731
01:13:49,124 --> 01:13:50,726
-Sung-hoon's honesty.
-That's the last one, the dessert.

1732
01:13:50,793 --> 01:13:52,928
Chef Yusuke made it in just one minute.

1733
01:13:52,995 --> 01:13:54,563
It may look too dirty, but please mix it.

1734
01:13:54,630 --> 01:13:56,899
He must be quite full by now.

1735
01:13:56,965 --> 01:13:58,600
This is the last dish.

1736
01:13:58,667 --> 01:14:00,536
ONE BIG BITE

1737
01:14:01,837 --> 01:14:03,305
HEY…

1738
01:14:03,372 --> 01:14:04,473
WHAT'S THIS RESPONSE?

1739
01:14:04,540 --> 01:14:06,341
-It must be sweet.
-What is it?

1740
01:14:06,408 --> 01:14:08,076
DID IT PASS HIS SWEETNESS BAR?

1741
01:14:08,143 --> 01:14:10,612
WHEN IT'S NOT SWEET, WHEN IT'S SWEET

1742
01:14:10,679 --> 01:14:13,282
-Desserts should be sweeter.
-Yes.

1743
01:14:13,348 --> 01:14:15,851
-I can taste the whipped cream,
-I see.

1744
01:14:15,918 --> 01:14:20,122
as well as the berries,
blueberries and all.

1745
01:14:20,189 --> 01:14:22,791
The bean paste is sweeter,
so everything goes well together.

1746
01:14:22,858 --> 01:14:24,893
-The red bean paste.
-The red bean paste.

1747
01:14:24,960 --> 01:14:27,262
Yogurt and whipped cream
must go well together.

1748
01:14:27,329 --> 01:14:29,798
-Gosh, look at him.
-And the red bean paste.

1749
01:14:29,865 --> 01:14:32,534
Japanese people are
good at using red bean paste.

1750
01:14:33,101 --> 01:14:34,636
HE EMPTIES IT OUT

1751
01:14:35,404 --> 01:14:38,073
Look at the amount of food he's eating.

1752
01:14:38,140 --> 01:14:40,175
He's like a detective who finally eats
after arresting someone.

1753
01:14:41,410 --> 01:14:44,146
-Gosh, that was a wonderful meal.
-He's like a veteran detective.

1754
01:14:46,782 --> 01:14:49,985
-It was delicious.
-It was great to see you enjoy it.

1755
01:14:50,052 --> 01:14:52,621
Please try Chef Jong-won's dish.

1756
01:14:53,188 --> 01:14:55,524
A BITE

1757
01:14:55,591 --> 01:14:58,560
This is the appetizer he made with eels.

1758
01:14:58,627 --> 01:15:02,698
It could've been a bit too greasy
with both eels and avocados,

1759
01:15:02,764 --> 01:15:05,167
but the pickled plum
balances out everything nicely.

1760
01:15:06,502 --> 01:15:08,837
-It's so good.
-I see.

1761
01:15:10,439 --> 01:15:11,940
I see.

1762
01:15:18,547 --> 01:15:19,548
I see.

1763
01:15:24,987 --> 01:15:25,988
A PROBLEM?

1764
01:15:27,422 --> 01:15:28,924
I see.

1765
01:15:31,927 --> 01:15:33,495
It was too little.

1766
01:15:33,562 --> 01:15:37,533
And now, we'll try
Chef Yusuke's noodle dish.

1767
01:15:39,501 --> 01:15:41,203
It's unlike my expectations.

1768
01:15:41,270 --> 01:15:43,839
-The soup is deep.
-It looks nutty,

1769
01:15:43,906 --> 01:15:45,974
yet it smells so refreshing.

1770
01:15:46,041 --> 01:15:47,476
My gosh.

1771
01:15:47,543 --> 01:15:49,177
-It's good.
-This is unique.

1772
01:15:49,244 --> 01:15:50,812
I see some tiny anchovies too.

1773
01:15:50,879 --> 01:15:53,949
It's like a mix between Japanese ramen

1774
01:15:54,016 --> 01:15:57,152
and Korean banquet noodles.

1775
01:16:05,594 --> 01:16:07,195
All right.

1776
01:16:07,262 --> 01:16:08,630
Okay, now.

1777
01:16:08,697 --> 01:16:11,133
-Are you asleep?
-It must be the sugar spike.

1778
01:16:11,199 --> 01:16:14,069
-The sugar spike got to him.
-The blood sugar spike?

1779
01:16:14,136 --> 01:16:16,171
I knew you'd do that
when you had too much to eat.

1780
01:16:16,238 --> 01:16:17,239
Are you asleep or thinking?

1781
01:16:17,306 --> 01:16:20,208
-I was thinking.
-Are you sure? Weren't you asleep?

1782
01:16:20,275 --> 01:16:23,545
I saw his eyes behind the glasses,
and they were closed.

1783
01:16:23,612 --> 01:16:25,647
-You were asleep.
-No way.

1784
01:16:25,714 --> 01:16:28,917
Lions go to sleep right away
as soon as they eat.

1785
01:16:28,984 --> 01:16:32,654
-Please choose either Yusuke or Jong-won.
-This is hard.

1786
01:16:32,721 --> 01:16:35,424
Press one for Chef Yusuke.

1787
01:16:35,490 --> 01:16:38,193
Press two for Son Jong-won.

1788
01:16:38,260 --> 01:16:41,396
Who will Sung-hoon choose
among these two chefs

1789
01:16:41,463 --> 01:16:44,600
-who represent Korea?
-This is so hard. It's because

1790
01:16:44,666 --> 01:16:47,235
-Chef Tanaka… Right. Takada.
-Takada.

1791
01:16:48,837 --> 01:16:50,372
-How many times has it been?
-Don't do that!

1792
01:16:50,439 --> 01:16:52,207
HOW MANY TIMES HAS IT BEEN?

1793
01:16:52,274 --> 01:16:54,176
Even Japanese people get it confused.

1794
01:16:54,242 --> 01:16:58,413
Jong-won's steak was
much better than this steak.

1795
01:16:58,480 --> 01:17:01,316
-It was definitely better.
-When it came to the taste?

1796
01:17:01,383 --> 01:17:04,853
But Chef Yusuke's dish had
something that you didn't.

1797
01:17:04,920 --> 01:17:07,723
I've been comparing the two.

1798
01:17:07,789 --> 01:17:09,858
Gosh, this is hard.

1799
01:17:09,925 --> 01:17:13,562
-You have to make your decision now.
-It's so hard.

1800
01:17:13,629 --> 01:17:15,697
HE RETRIES CHEF JONG-WON'S DISH

1801
01:17:15,764 --> 01:17:17,466
He tries the dishes again.

1802
01:17:17,532 --> 01:17:19,901
-He's eating the veggies.
-He tries the veggies now.

1803
01:17:21,770 --> 01:17:22,971
HE HAD A BITE, AND THEN DECIDED?

1804
01:17:23,038 --> 01:17:25,407
-Have you decided?
-He has decided.

1805
01:17:25,474 --> 01:17:29,878
Press one for Chef Yusuke.
Pres two for Chef Jong-won.

1806
01:17:29,945 --> 01:17:33,215
Make your decision and press the button!

1807
01:17:33,281 --> 01:17:34,850
This is Sung-hoon's choice.

1808
01:17:35,784 --> 01:17:37,152
HE MADE HIS CHOICE

1809
01:17:37,219 --> 01:17:41,123
-He made his decision.
-This is so hard.

1810
01:17:41,189 --> 01:17:42,190
I pushed it.

1811
01:17:42,257 --> 01:17:45,427
This was the final round.

1812
01:17:45,494 --> 01:17:47,763
Who'll be the last one standing?

1813
01:17:48,597 --> 01:17:52,134
This round was called Sexy Food: Protein.

1814
01:17:52,200 --> 01:17:56,171
Son Jong-won, who runs
two one-star Michelin restaurants.

1815
01:17:56,238 --> 01:17:58,607
Takada Yusuke, who runs
a two-star Michelin restaurant.

1816
01:17:58,674 --> 01:18:00,575
-Who did Sung-hoon choose?
-Who is it?

1817
01:18:00,642 --> 01:18:02,277
Which one is it?

1818
01:18:02,344 --> 01:18:05,714
Who'll be the winner?

1819
01:18:05,781 --> 01:18:07,916
-Who's the winner?
-Who's the winner?

1820
01:18:07,983 --> 01:18:09,651
Who did Sung-hoon choose?

1821
01:18:11,820 --> 01:18:13,188
Who did Sung-hoon choose?

1822
01:18:13,255 --> 01:18:16,425
CHEF YUSUKE'S TAKADA-LICIOUS WINS

1823
01:18:16,992 --> 01:18:20,896
CHEF YUSUKE WAS THE KING OF PROTEIN

1824
01:18:21,463 --> 01:18:23,532
THAT WAS CLOSE

1825
01:18:23,598 --> 01:18:25,333
-He was very nervous.
-He was.

1826
01:18:25,400 --> 01:18:28,470
The moment he saw the result,
he clenched his fists hard.

1827
01:18:28,537 --> 01:18:32,441
-First of all, my order was protein.
-Yes.

1828
01:18:32,507 --> 01:18:36,712
I began to consider
which one of them had more protein.

1829
01:18:36,778 --> 01:18:37,779
The amount of protein.

1830
01:18:37,846 --> 01:18:40,882
And Chef Yusuke served
much more protein than the other.

1831
01:18:40,949 --> 01:18:44,252
In the end,
I just need to eat lots of protein.

1832
01:18:44,319 --> 01:18:46,488
-It was the quantity?
-That was why.

1833
01:18:46,555 --> 01:18:49,624
He lost because of the quantity.

1834
01:18:49,691 --> 01:18:52,627
Let us hear from you, Chef Yusuke.

1835
01:18:52,694 --> 01:18:54,830
There is no winning and losing in cooking,

1836
01:18:54,896 --> 01:18:56,998
but I hope these opportunities help

1837
01:18:57,065 --> 01:18:59,367
Korea and Japan
continue to connect like this.

1838
01:18:59,434 --> 01:19:02,437
Please put a star on Chef Yusuke.

1839
01:19:04,106 --> 01:19:05,707
WE THANK THE CHEFS
FOR THE WONDERFUL PERFORMANCE

1840
01:19:05,774 --> 01:19:09,745
Chef Yusuke is the winner.
Congratulations!

1841
01:19:10,245 --> 01:19:11,346
Congratulations.

1842
01:19:11,413 --> 01:19:13,548
STAY TUNED FOR NEXT WEEK'S FRIDGE OWNERS,
HOSHI, WOOZI, AND MIMI

1843
01:19:13,615 --> 01:19:17,185
Idols celebrating their tenth anniversary,
HOSHI and WOOZI of SEVENTEEN!

1844
01:19:17,252 --> 01:19:18,854
And please welcome Mimi of OH MY GIRL!

1845
01:19:18,920 --> 01:19:21,490
I hear their team dinner costs
ten million won.

1846
01:19:21,556 --> 01:19:23,325
Our appetite is beyond your imagination.

1847
01:19:23,391 --> 01:19:25,694
Just come. I'll steam, stir-fry,
roast, and everything else.

1848
01:19:25,761 --> 01:19:27,028
He's one of my family.

1849
01:19:27,095 --> 01:19:28,230
-His family?
-We're family.

1850
01:19:28,296 --> 01:19:29,564
Why are you going down that road?

1851
01:19:29,631 --> 01:19:30,932
It's an honor for us.

1852
01:19:30,999 --> 01:19:33,268
This will be a bloody fight.

1853
01:19:33,335 --> 01:19:35,403
<i>I wanted to express</i>
<i>SEVENTEEN in this dish.</i>

1854
01:19:35,470 --> 01:19:37,405
<i>It's a dish to celebrate</i>
<i>their tenth anniversary.</i>

1855
01:19:37,472 --> 01:19:39,574
-He's putting it into one.
-This is so cool.

1856
01:19:39,641 --> 01:19:40,809
He put it in!

1857
01:19:40,876 --> 01:19:42,477
Fabri from Italy

1858
01:19:42,544 --> 01:19:44,312
versus Kim Sohyi from Vienna.

1859
01:19:44,379 --> 01:19:46,448
I love Western cuisine,
but I always need kimchi.

1860
01:19:46,515 --> 01:19:47,516
That's radish kimchi.

1861
01:19:47,582 --> 01:19:49,017
<i>Kimchi, nice</i>

1862
01:19:49,084 --> 01:19:51,186
Look how well they're eating.

1863
01:19:51,253 --> 01:19:53,121
-They look happy as they eat.
-It looks so good.

1864
01:19:53,188 --> 01:19:54,623
The result is one to one.

1865
01:19:54,689 --> 01:19:55,791
AN UNPRECEDENTED SITUATION ON THE SHOW?

1866
01:19:55,857 --> 01:19:57,959
Come on. Don't do that.

1867
01:19:58,026 --> 01:20:00,796
Jeez. Why do you say that?

1868
01:20:12,140 --> 01:20:16,912
Subtitle translation by: Eunsook Youn
